 = = Reception = = 
 
 The game received positive reviews upon release . The <unk> version holds an aggregate score of 86 % from GameRankings , whereas the Game Boy Advance version holds a score of 76 % . 
 The graphics and gameplay were the most praised aspects of the game . Frank <unk> of GameSpot stated that the graphics were colourful , vibrant and " top @-@ notch " . Lucas Thomas of IGN opined that Dixie Kong 's Double Trouble ! ' s visuals were not as <unk> @-@ inspiring as the pre @-@ rendered CGI of <unk> Kong Country , however he admitted that they " still looked great " for the third instalment . In a retrospective review , <unk> van <unk> of <unk> praised the game 's visuals and detailed backgrounds , stating that they were " fantastic " for the <unk> . Reviewing the Game Boy Advance version , a reviewer from GamePro thought that the graphics appeared " washed out " on the system 's <unk> screen ; stating that the pre @-@ rendered sprites did not " show up very well " . A reviewer from Nintendo Master thought that the game 's main strengths were its " beautiful graphics and script " . A reviewer from <unk> asserted that the various aspects of gameplay made Dixie Kong 's Double Trouble ! a hallmark of the series . 
 The music received mixed opinions from critics . Although <unk> stated that the game 's music was " catchy " , he noted that devotees to the original <unk> Kong Country may not like it . Thomas thought compared to the other <unk> Kong Country games , the music in Dixie Kong 's Double Trouble ! stands out the least , although he stated that it was an " impressive effort " . Van <unk> similarly stated that the soundtrack was not as " legendary " as it was in its previous instalment , however he still admitted that it had some " great " tracks . In addition , Van <unk> criticised the Game Boy Advance 's port for replacing all of the original music with remixed versions . However , <unk> stated that the music was " just as good " as the original , regarding the soundtrack on the Game Boy Advance port . 
 
 
 = Herb <unk> = 
 
 Herbert <unk> <unk> ( February 10 , 1894 – January 30 , 1948 ) was an American professional baseball pitcher . He played in Major League Baseball from 1912 through 1933 . He is best known for his time spent with the star @-@ studded New York Yankee teams of the mid to late 1920s and early 1930s . 
 Connie Mack signed <unk> to his Philadelphia Athletics in 1912 . After using <unk> <unk> , and questioning his competitive drive , Mack sold <unk> to the Boston Red Sox in 1915 . After returning from military service in 1919 , <unk> became a regular contributor for the Red Sox . The Yankees acquired <unk> from the Red Sox after the 1922 season , and he served as a key member of the pitching staff as the Yankees won four World Series championships during his tenure with the team . After retiring as a player , <unk> served as a coach and farm system director for the Red Sox , and as general manager of the Philadelphia Phillies . 
 <unk> was regarded as one of the greatest left @-@ handed pitchers in baseball history . Mack later called his sale of <unk> to the Red Sox his greatest mistake . <unk> died of a <unk> <unk> in 1948 ; later that year , he was posthumously inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame . 
 
 = = Early life = = 
 
 <unk> was born on February 10 , 1894 in <unk> Square , Pennsylvania . His father , Theodore <unk> , and mother Mary Louise <unk> ( née Sharp ) were of Scotch @-@ Irish and Quaker descent . His ancestors came to the United States with William Penn . Herb was the youngest of four children . 
 <unk> attended <unk> School and <unk> <unk> School , where he played for the baseball team . After struggling as a first baseman , with a weak offensive output and throwing arm that resulted in curved throws , his <unk> coach converted <unk> into a pitcher . 
 
 = = Playing career = = 
 
 
 = = = Philadelphia Athletics = = = 
 
 While pitching at <unk> , <unk> threw a no @-@ hitter to catcher <unk> Mack , the son of Connie Mack , manager of the Philadelphia Athletics , in 1910 . <unk> agreed to sign with the Athletics at a later date . Mack signed <unk> in 1912 to play for his collegiate team based in Atlantic City . <unk> 's father insisted that he sign under an <unk> in order to protect his collegiate eligibility . <unk> threw a no @-@ hitter against a traveling <unk> league baseball team , and Mack promoted him to the Athletics . Mack intended for <unk> to be one of the prospects who would replace star pitchers Eddie Plank , Chief <unk> , and Jack Coombs . 
 <unk> made his major league debut with the Athletics during the 1912 season on May 14 , allowing one hit in four innings pitched . He was the youngest person to play in the American League ( AL ) that season . Former major <unk> Mike Grady , a neighbor of <unk> 's in <unk> Square , took <unk> under his wing , while <unk> taught <unk> to throw a <unk> . 
 <unk> missed most of the 1913 season with an illness . In the 1914 season , <unk> posted an 11 – 4 win – loss record with a 2 @.@ 79 earned run average ( ERA ) in 151 2 ⁄ 3 innings pitched for the Athletics , and pitched three scoreless innings in the 1914 World Series , which the Athletics lost to the Boston Braves . Mack let <unk> go after the season , naming <unk> his Opening Day starting pitcher in 1915 . On Opening Day , <unk> threw a one @-@ hit complete game shutout against the Boston Red Sox . However , as the Athletics struggled , <unk> 's <unk> playing style drew Mack 's ire . <unk> that <unk> " lacked ambition " , Mack sold <unk> to the Red Sox for the <unk> price of $ 2 @,@ 500 ( $ 58 @,@ <unk> in current dollar terms ) . Mack later regarded this sale as his greatest mistake . 
 
 = = = Boston Red Sox = = = 
 
 With a deep pitching staff in place , the Red Sox loaned <unk> to the Providence Grays of the International League in August for the remainder of the 1915 season . He split the 1916 season between the Red Sox and the Buffalo <unk> , also in the International League . With Buffalo , <unk> pitched to a 1 @.@ 67 ERA , as Buffalo won the league pennant . Though the Red Sox won the 1915 and 1916 World Series , <unk> did not appear in either series . 
 Pitching in minor league baseball , <unk> began to regain confidence . However , Boston manager Jack Barry used <unk> <unk> in the 1917 season , and <unk> enlisted in the United States Navy in 1918 . <unk> pitched for a team fielded by the Navy , defeating a team composed of members of the United States Army in an exhibition for George VI , the King of England , in Stamford Bridge . After the game , Ed Barrow , the new manager of the Red Sox , signed <unk> to a new contract after promising to use him regularly during the 1919 season . 
 <unk> received only one start apiece in the months of April and May , as the 1919 Red Sox relied on George <unk> , Bill James , and Bullet Joe Bush , leading <unk> to threaten to quit in late @-@ May unless Barrow fulfilled his earlier promise to <unk> . Barrow continued to use <unk> regularly after Memorial Day , and <unk> finished the season with a 16 – 8 win @-@ loss record and a 2 @.@ 71 ERA in 219 innings pitched . He served as the team 's ace pitcher in the 1920 season , but subsequently settled in as the Red Sox ' third starter . After the 1922 Red Sox campaign , in which he went 10 – 17 , and had seven wild pitches , leading the AL , the New York Yankees began to negotiate with the Red Sox to acquire <unk> . The Yankees traded <unk> McMillan , George Murray , and Camp Skinner to the Red Sox for <unk> that offseason . 
 
 = = = New York Yankees = = = 
 
 <unk> pitched to a 19 – 6 win @-@ loss record in the 1923 season , his first with the Yankees , leading the American League ( AL ) in winning percentage ( <unk> ) and finishing sixth in wins . Pitching in the 1923 World Series , <unk> defeated the New York Giants in game two , on October 11 , to end their eight @-@ game World Series winning streak . He recorded a save in securing the Yankees ' win in game four , and pitched to the win in game six on one day of rest , <unk> the Yankees ' first World Series championship . <unk> Billy Evans called it " the greatest pitching performance I have ever seen " , as <unk> " had nothing . " 
 In the 1924 season , he pitched to a 21 – 9 win @-@ loss record with a 2 @.@ 83 ERA while striking out a career @-@ high 101 batters . His win total was second in the AL , behind Walter Johnson , while his ERA was third behind Johnson and Tom Zachary , and he finished fourth in strikeouts behind Johnson , Howard <unk> , and teammate Bob <unk> . <unk> 's 277 innings pitched and 1 @.@ 220 walks plus hits per inning pitched ( <unk> ) ratio led the AL in the 1925 season , while his 2 @.@ 96 ERA was second @-@ best , behind Stan <unk> . In the 1926 season , he posted a career @-@ high 23 wins , finishing second in the AL to George <unk> . He again led the AL in <unk> ( 1 @.@ 265 ) , and issued the fewest walks per nine innings pitched ( 1 @.@ 453 ) . During the pennant race , The Sporting News called <unk> the " best left @-@ <unk> in the majors " . <unk> earned the wins in game one and game five of the 1926 World Series . He finished game seven of the series , which the Yankees lost to the St. Louis Cardinals . 
 The Yankees reached the World Series , facing the Pittsburgh Pirates . <unk> pitched a complete game against the Pirates in game three of the 1927 World Series , not allowing a hit until the eighth inning . <unk> 's performance drew praise from teammate Babe Ruth . The Yankees swept the series from Pittsburgh . After pitching a three @-@ hit shutout against the Red Sox on August 12 , 1928 , he missed the remainder of the season , including the 1928 World Series , with an arm injury . His five <unk> and 0 @.@ <unk> home runs per nine innings pitched led the AL . His 2 @.@ 56 ERA trailed only Garland <unk> , while his 17 wins tied for eighth place . Though the Yankees defeated the Cardinals in the 1928 World Series , the Yankees ' starting rotation without <unk> was likened to " a three @-@ <unk> <unk> . " 
 In the 1929 season , <unk> saw his pitching time and pitching quality <unk> . Over the rest of his career , he never posted more than 189 innings pitched in a season and his ERA rose to over 4 @.@ 00 . He suffered from bouts of <unk> in 1929 and 1930 . <unk> won his 200th career game during the 1929 season , becoming the third left @-@ handed pitcher to reach that mark . He led the AL in walks per nine innings pitched in 1930 ( 1 @.@ 151 ) and 1931 ( 1 @.@ 426 ) . <unk> pitched four innings of relief against the Chicago Cubs in the 1932 World Series , recording two saves . The New York chapter of the Baseball Writers ' Association of America named him their player of the year . 
 In 1933 , serving exclusively as a relief pitcher , <unk> had a 7 – 4 win @-@ loss record in 23 appearances . After the 1933 season , the Yankees honored <unk> with a testimonial dinner on January 6 , 1934 , and then gave him his release . 
 
 = = = Return to Boston = = = 
 
 Eddie Collins , a former teammate with the Athletics now serving as the general manager of the Red Sox , signed <unk> to their 1934 roster . In his last season pitching in the major leagues , <unk> served as a relief pitcher for the Red Sox . 
 <unk> retired with a career record of 240 wins , 162 losses , and a 3 @.@ 60 ERA . <unk> pitched in five World Series , one with Philadelphia and four with New York . He was a member of four World Series championship teams . In World Series play , <unk> amassed a 5 – 0 career win @-@ loss record with three saves , becoming the second pitcher to win five World Series games , after Coombs . <unk> was a part of seven World Series championship teams ( 1913 , 1915 , 1916 , 1923 , 1927 , 1928 , and 1932 ) , though he played in four World Series ' as a member of the winning team . Many , including Mack , consider <unk> among the greatest left @-@ handed pitchers of all time . 
 
 = = Post @-@ playing career = = 
 
 <unk> became the general manager of the Charlotte Hornets , a Red Sox ' farm team of the <unk> League , prior to the 1935 season . He returned to the Red Sox in 1936 , serving as the first base and pitching coach under manager Joe <unk> . He served in this role through the 1938 season . In 1939 , <unk> served as the Assistant Supervisor of Boston 's minor league system , reporting to Evans . <unk> succeeded Evans as Director of Minor League Operations late in the 1940 season . 
 In December 1943 , R. R. M. Carpenter , Jr . , the new owner of the Philadelphia Phillies , hired <unk> as his general manager , after receiving a recommendation from Mack . Carpenter gave <unk> a lifetime contract . <unk> filled Carpenter 's duties when the team 's owner was drafted into service during World War II in 1944 . As general manager , <unk> changed the team 's name to the " Blue Jays " , and invested $ 1 million ( $ 13 @,@ <unk> @,@ 344 in current dollar terms ) into players who would become known as the " <unk> Kids " , who won the National League pennant in 1950 , including Curt Simmons and Willie Jones . He also created a " <unk> <unk> Club " , the first in baseball history , allowing fans to give feedback to the team , and advocated for the repeal of the <unk> Rule . 
 <unk> opposed racial integration in baseball . In 1947 , when Jackie Robinson was signed to the Brooklyn Dodgers , <unk> called Dodgers team president Branch <unk> before the Dodgers ' series in Philadelphia and told him not to " bring that <unk> here with the rest of the team . " He further threatened to boycott a 1947 game between the Phillies and Dodgers if Robinson played . 
 In 1948 , at the age of 53 , one week and four days before his 54th birthday , <unk> collapsed in the lobby of the Waldorf @-@ Astoria Hotel as a result of a <unk> <unk> . He was pronounced dead upon his arrival at <unk> Hospital . <unk> had been healthy , even inviting friends to join him at Madison Square Garden to attend a boxing match . 
 
