 = <unk> , Montana = 
 
 <unk> / <unk> / is a city in the U.S. state of Montana and is the county seat of <unk> County . It is located along the Clark Fork River near its <unk> with the <unk> and Blackfoot Rivers in western Montana and at the convergence of five mountain ranges , thus is often described as the " hub of five valleys " . In 2015 , the United States Census Bureau estimated the city 's population at 71 @,@ <unk> and the population of the <unk> Metropolitan Area at 114 @,@ 181 . In the 1990s , <unk> overtook Great Falls as Montana ’ s second ‑ largest city , behind <unk> . <unk> is home to the University of Montana , a public research university . 
 <unk> was founded in 1860 as <unk> Trading Post while still part of Washington Territory . By 1866 , the settlement had moved east , 5 miles ( 8 km ) upstream , and renamed <unk> Mills , later shortened to <unk> . The mills provided supplies to western settlers traveling along the <unk> Road . The establishment of Fort <unk> in 1877 to protect settlers further stabilized the economy . The arrival of the Northern Pacific Railway in 1883 brought rapid growth and the maturation of the local lumber industry . In 1893 , the Montana Legislature chose the city as the site for the state 's first university . Along with the U.S. Forest Service headquarters founded in 1908 , lumber and the university remained staples of the local economy for the next hundred years . 
 By the 1990s , <unk> 's lumber industry had gradually disappeared , and as of 2009 , the city 's largest employers were the University of Montana , <unk> County Public Schools , and <unk> 's two hospitals . The city is governed by a mayor – council government with twelve city council members , two from each of the six wards . In and around <unk> are 400 acres ( 160 ha ) of <unk> , 22 miles ( 35 km ) of trails , and nearly 5 @,@ 000 acres ( 2 @,@ 000 ha ) of open @-@ space conservation land with adjacent Mount Jumbo home to grazing elk and mule deer during the winter . The city is also home to both Montana 's largest and its oldest active <unk> as well as the Montana <unk> , one of the strongest college football programs in the Division I Football Championship <unk> of the National Collegiate Athletic Association ( NCAA ) . Notable residents include the first woman in the U.S. Congress , <unk> Rankin , and the United States ' longest @-@ serving Senate Majority Leader , Mike Mansfield . 
 
 = = History = = 
 
 Archaeological artifacts date the <unk> Valley 's earliest inhabitants to the end of the last ice age 12 @,@ 000 years ago with settlements as early as <unk> BCE . From the <unk> until European settlements began a hundred years later , it was primarily the <unk> , <unk> , <unk> d <unk> , <unk> , and Shoshone who used the land . Located at the confluence of five mountain valleys , the <unk> Valley was heavily <unk> by local and distant native tribes that periodically went to the Eastern Montana plains in search of bison , leading to conflict . The narrow valley at <unk> 's eastern entrance was so <unk> with human bones from repeated ambushes that French fur trappers would later refer to this area as <unk> de l <unk> , translated as " Gate of Hell " . Hell Gate would remain the name of the area until it was renamed " <unk> " in 1866 . 
 The Lewis and Clark Expedition brought the first U.S. citizens to the area . They twice stopped just south of <unk> at Traveler 's Rest . They camped there the first time on their westbound trip in September 1805 . When they stayed there again on their return in June – July 1806 , Clark left heading south along the <unk> River and Lewis traveled north , then east , through <unk> Canyon . In 1860 , Hell Gate Village was established 5 miles ( 8 km ) west of present @-@ day downtown by Christopher P. Higgins and Frank <unk> as a trading post to serve travelers on the recently completed <unk> Road , the first wagon road to cross the Rocky Mountains to the inland of the Pacific Northwest . The desire for a more convenient water supply to power a lumber and flour mill led to the movement of the settlement to its modern location in 1864 . 
 The <unk> Mills replaced Hell Gate Village as the economic power of the valley and replaced it as the county seat in 1866 . The name " <unk> " came from the <unk> name for the Clark Fork River , " <unk> " , which roughly translates as " place of frozen water " . Fort <unk> was established in 1877 to help protect further arriving settlers . Growth accelerated with the arrival of the Northern Pacific Railway in 1883 , and the Town of <unk> was chartered the same year . In 1893 , <unk> was chosen as the location of the state 's first university , the University of Montana . The need for lumber for the railway and its bridges spurred the opening of multiple saw mills in the area and , in turn , the beginning of <unk> 's lumber industry , which remained the mainstay of the area 's economy for the next hundred years . The continued economic <unk> from railroad construction and lumber mills led to a further boom in <unk> 's population . A. B. Hammond and <unk> Kings Marcus Daly and William A. Clark competed fiercely in the region over lumber share and <unk> investments . The United States Forest Service work in <unk> began in 1905 . <unk> is also home of the <unk> ' headquarters and will be the site of the National Museum of Forest Service History . <unk> , there are nine Forest Service regions ; Region 1 is headquartered in <unk> . 
 <unk> remained a mainstay of industry in <unk> with the groundbreaking of the <unk> @-@ Waldorf pulp mill in 1956 , which resulted in protests over the resultant air pollution . An article in Life magazine thirteen years later speaks of <unk> sometimes needing to drive with <unk> on during the day to navigate through the <unk> . In 1979 , still almost 40 % of the county 's labor income came from the wood and paper products sector . The lumber industry was hit hard by the recession of the early 1980s , and <unk> 's economy began to <unk> . By the early 1990s , the disappearance of many of the region 's log yards , along with legislation , had helped clean the skies dramatically . 
 As of 2009 , education and healthcare were <unk> 's leading industries ; the University of Montana , <unk> County Public Schools , and the city 's two hospitals were the largest employers . St. Patrick Hospital and Health Sciences Center , founded in 1873 , is the region 's only Level II trauma center and has undergone three major expansions since the 1980s . Likewise , the University of Montana grew 50 % and built or renovated 20 buildings from 1990 – 2010 . It is expected that these industries as well as expansions in business and professional services , and retail will be the main engines of future growth . 
 
 = = Geography = = 
 
 <unk> is located at the western edge of Montana approximately 45 miles ( 70 km ) from the Idaho border . The city is at an elevation of 3 @,@ <unk> feet ( 978 m ) above sea level , with nearby Mount Sentinel and Mount Jumbo steeply rising to 5 @,@ 158 feet ( 1 @,@ <unk> m ) and 4 @,@ <unk> feet ( 1 @,@ 453 m ) respectively . According to the Census Bureau 's 2015 figures , the city had a total area of 29 @.@ 08 square miles ( 75 @.@ 3 km2 ) , of which , 28 @.@ 90 square miles ( 74 @.@ 9 km2 ) was land and 0 @.@ 184 square miles ( 0 @.@ 48 km2 ) was water . 
 Approximately 13 @,@ 000 years ago , the entire valley was at the bottom of <unk> Lake <unk> and as could be expected for a former lake bottom , the layout of <unk> is relatively flat and surrounded by steep hills . Evidence of the city of <unk> 's lake @-@ bottom past can be seen in the form of ancient horizontal wave @-@ cut <unk> on nearby Mount Sentinel and Mount Jumbo . At the location of present @-@ day University of Montana , the lake once had a depth of 950 feet ( 290 m ) . The Clark Fork River enters the <unk> Valley from the east through <unk> Canyon after joining the nearby Blackfoot River at the site of the former <unk> Dam . The <unk> River and multiple smaller tributaries join the Clark Fork on the western edge of <unk> . The city also sits at the convergence of five mountain ranges : the <unk> Mountains , <unk> Range , <unk> Range , <unk> Mountains , and the <unk> Divide , thus is often described as being the " hub of five valleys " . 
 
 = = = Flora and fauna = = = 
 
 Located in the Northern Rockies , <unk> has a typical Rocky Mountain ecology . Local wildlife includes populations of white @-@ tailed deer , black bears , <unk> , and bald eagles . During the winter , rapid snowmelt on Mount Jumbo due to its steep slope leaves grass available for grazing elk and mule deer . The rivers around <unk> provide nesting habitats for bank swallows , northern rough @-@ winged swallows and <unk> <unk> . <unk> and spotted <unk> can be seen foraging for insects along the gravel bars . Other species include song <unk> , <unk> , several species of <unk> , and the <unk> <unk> . The rivers also provide cold , clean water for native fish such as <unk> <unk> trout and bull trout . The <unk> streams also attract beaver and wood ducks . The parks also host a variety of snakes such as <unk> , <unk> snakes , and rubber <unk> . 
 Native riparian plant life includes <unk> willows and <unk> with Montana 's state tree , the ponderosa pine , also being prevalent . Other native plants include wetland species such as <unk> and <unk> @-@ <unk> as well as shrubs and <unk> plants like Douglas hawthorn , <unk> , and western <unk> . To the <unk> of local farmers , <unk> is also home to several <unk> weeds , which multiple programs have set out to eliminate . Notable ones include <unk> <unk> , spotted <unk> , leafy <unk> , St. John 's <unk> , and sulfur <unk> . <unk> , the Norway <unk> that line many of <unk> 's older streets have also been declared an invasive species . 
 
 = = = Climate = = = 
 
 <unk> has a semi @-@ arid climate ( Köppen climate classification <unk> ) , with cold and moderately <unk> winters , hot and dry summers , and short , <unk> springs and <unk> . Winters are usually <unk> than much of the rest of the state due to its location west of the Rockies , allowing it to be influenced more by mild , moist Pacific air and avoiding the worst of cold snaps ; however , this means precipitation is not at a strong minimum during winter . Winter snowfall averages 39 @.@ 5 inches ( 100 cm ) , on average occurring between October 30 and April 20 . As with the rest of the state , summers are very sunny , and the average diurnal temperature variation is more than 30 ° F ( 17 ° C ) from late June through late September , due to the relative <unk> . The monthly daily average temperature ranges from 23 @.@ 9 ° F ( − 4 @.@ 5 ° C ) in December to 68 @.@ 6 ° F ( 20 @.@ 3 ° C ) in July . There is an average of 24 days with temperatures above 90 ° F ( 32 ° C ) , 45 days where the temperature does not rise above freezing , and 7 @.@ 8 days with temperatures below 0 ° F ( − 18 ° C ) . 
 
 = = Demographics = = 
 
 The median income for a household in the city was $ 30 @,@ 366 , and the median income for a family was $ 42 @,@ 103 . Males had a median income of $ 30 @,@ <unk> versus $ 21 @,@ <unk> for females . The per capita income for the city was $ 17 @,@ 166 . About 11 @.@ 7 % of families and 19 @.@ 7 % of the population were below the poverty line , including 20 @.@ 5 % of those under age 18 and 9 @.@ 3 % of those age 65 or over . 40 @.@ 3 % of <unk> residents age 25 and older have a bachelor 's or advanced college degree . 
 
 = = = 2010 census = = = 
 
 As of 2010 's census , there were 66 @,@ <unk> people , 29 @,@ 081 households , and 13 @,@ 990 families residing in the city . The population density was 2 @,@ <unk> @.@ 8 inhabitants per square mile ( <unk> @.@ 4 / km2 ) . There were 30 @,@ 682 housing units at an average density of 1 @,@ 115 @.@ 3 per square mile ( 430 @.@ 6 / km2 ) . The racial makeup of the city was 92 @.@ 1 % White , 0 @.@ 5 % African American , 2 @.@ 8 % Native American , 1 @.@ 2 % Asian , 0 @.@ 1 % Pacific Islander , 0 @.@ 5 % from other races , and 2 @.@ 8 % from two or more races . Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2 @.@ 9 % of the population . 
 There were 29 @,@ 081 households of which 23 @.@ 6 % had children under the age of 18 living with them , 34 @.@ 4 % were married couples living together , 9 @.@ 6 % had a female <unk> with no husband present , 4 @.@ 1 % had a male <unk> with no wife present , and 51 @.@ 9 % were non @-@ families . 35 @.@ 0 % of all households were made up of individuals and 9 @.@ 1 % had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older . The average household size was 2 @.@ 18 and the average family size was 2 @.@ 82 . 
 The median age in the city was 30 @.@ 9 years . 17 @.@ 9 % of residents were under the age of 18 ; 19 @.@ 7 % were between the ages of 18 and 24 ; 29 @.@ 6 % were from 25 to 44 ; 22 @.@ 1 % were from 45 to 64 ; and 10 @.@ 7 % were 65 years of age or older . The gender makeup of the city was 49 @.@ 9 % male and 50 @.@ 1 % female . 
 
 = = Economy = = 
 
 <unk> began as a trading post in the 1860s situated along the <unk> Military Road to take advantage of the first route across the <unk> Mountains to the plains of Eastern Washington . Its designation as county seat in 1866 and location of the hastily built Fort <unk> in 1877 ensured <unk> 's status as a regional commercial center ; a status further consolidated in 1883 with the arrival of the Northern Pacific Railway . The railroad expanded <unk> 's trade area to cover a 150 @-@ mile radius , and <unk> 's location as the railway 's division point and repair shops provided hundreds of jobs . When the railway began expanding again in 1898 , increased freight shipments came through the city , and with the arrival of the Milwaukee Road and regional office for the U.S. Forest Service as well as the opening of the <unk> Indian <unk> to settlement all within a couple years of each other beginning in 1908 , the economy began to rapidly expand . 
 Lumber mills , originally built to provide construction @-@ grade materials for homes and business but then expanded to entice and then meet the demands of the railroad , <unk> from an increase in demand from railroad expansion and the nation at large . The <unk> mill , owned the Northern Pacific and <unk> King Marcus Daly , became the largest producer of lumber in the northwest . In 1908 , <unk> 's location as both a major lumber producer and a regional commercial center helped land the city the regional office for the newly establish U.S. Forest Service created to help manage the nation 's timber supply . Over the next century , <unk> 's various lumber industries was consolidated under various entities such as the <unk> Company in the 1970s and Champion International Paper through the 1980s until most were under control of Plum Creek <unk> , all the while demand in timber dropped . In 2007 , a downward spiral of <unk> 's lumber industry began with the closure of a <unk> plant in <unk> , the closure of <unk> 's sawmill in 2008 , and the closing of the <unk> @-@ Stone <unk> pulp mill in 2010 . 
 Since opening in 1895 , the University of Montana has had a major impact on the development of <unk> 's economy . In addition to the economic advantage from <unk> the student body , it gave the city an educated workforce not available in most of the state . The university has a close relationship with the city as <unk> 's largest employer and with the millions of dollars the school brings into the city through visitors of school @-@ sponsored sporting and cultural events . The university also houses <unk> 's only business <unk> , the Montana Technology Enterprise Center ( <unk> ) , and several start @-@ up businesses . 
 Beyond timber and education , <unk> 's economic mainstay has been of one as a regional trade center . <unk> has an immediate trade area of approximately 180 @,@ 000 residents . The <unk> is the hub of its Bureau of Economic Analysis ( <unk> ) Economic Area , which includes the Montana Counties of <unk> , Lake , Lincoln , Mineral , <unk> , <unk> , and Sanders . As of 2011 , the <unk> listed the economic area population at <unk> @,@ 050 . Key businesses sectors serving the area include health care , retail shopping , transportation , financial services , government and social services , education , events , arts and culture . Health care in particular is one of <unk> 's fastest growing industries with St. Patrick Hospital ( western Montana 's only Level II <unk> center ) and the Community Medical Center already the city 's second and third largest employers behind the university . 55 % of employment in <unk> is made up of the service and retail sectors . <unk> industries are concentrated in heavy and civil engineering , construction , <unk> production , technical services , truck transportation , and <unk> , <unk> , and wood @-@ related industries . In addition to nearly 4 million out @-@ of @-@ state visitors annually , which makes tourism a significant aspect of the <unk> economy , <unk> also is home to a vibrant sector of alternative healthcare . 
 As of 2013 , <unk> ranked <unk> nationally in gross metropolitan product with an output of $ 5 billion , while the city 's total personal income ranked 333 at $ 4 @.@ 18 billion , an increase of more than 47 % since 2003 . As of 2013 , per capita personal income ranked 239 at $ 37 @,@ <unk> a year , 84 % of the national average . The <unk> metropolitan area 's unemployment rate was 3 @.@ 7 % As of June 2015 , dropping nearly 0 @.@ 8 % in the twelve months prior . 
 
 = = Culture = = 
 
 <unk> , often considered the cultural center of Montana , is the location of the state 's first university , and an eclectic mix of loggers , <unk> , college students , sports fans , and <unk> . Community events generally take place downtown either outdoors or in one of the several downtown buildings listed on the National Historic <unk> . 
 Since 2006 , the River City Roots Festival has been an event each August with music , beer , food , and art , and generally attracts crowds of 15 @,@ 000 . The longest @-@ standing event downtown has been the <unk> <unk> Market that was founded in 1972 , which provides an outlet for Western Montana produce on Saturday mornings from May to October as well as Tuesday evenings from July to early September . An arts and crafts People 's Market and a Clark Fork Market run concurrently . Downtown hosts " First Friday <unk> " , a gallery walk on the first Friday of the month to feature local art from museums and galleries , such as that of Monte <unk> . <unk> celebrates " First Night <unk> " on New Year 's Eve , which includes food and live entertainment . The " Festival of the Book " to celebrate the literature of the American West was rebranded the " Montana Book Festival " in 2015 . <unk> 's two historic theatres both hold annual film festivals : the Roxy hosting the International Wildlife Film Festival , established in 1977 as the first <unk> wildlife film festival in the world ; and since 2003 , the <unk> <unk> the largest film event in Montana , the Big Sky Documentary Film Festival . In performance arts , the <unk> Community Theatre has held performances of musical and non @-@ musical plays since 1977 , with its affiliated <unk> Children 's Theatre also acting as an international touring program that visits nearly 1 @,@ 000 communities per year around the world . 
 The Montana Museum of Art & Culture , which became a state museum in 2001 , is one Montana 's oldest cultural reserves , having begun in 1894 ; its permanent collection of more than 10 @,@ 000 original works . The <unk> Museum of Art is housed in a former Carnegie library ; it features contemporary art and annually features 20 – 25 group and solo exhibits . Fort <unk> is home to the Historic Museum , dedicated to preserving the history of Western Montana , and to the Rocky Mountain Museum of Military History and the Northern Rockies Heritage Center . The National Museum of Forest Service History is constructing the National Conservation Legacy and Education Center in <unk> as well . 
 <unk> in 1987 , <unk> 's Bayern <unk> is the oldest active <unk> in Montana . Big Sky <unk> opened in 1995 and with a production of over 38 @,@ 000 barrels in 2008 , it is by far Montana 's largest <unk> , and produces the best @-@ selling beer <unk> in Montana , Moose <unk> Brown <unk> . <unk> has also been home to <unk> House <unk> since 1995 and <unk> Works opened in 2011 . Big Sky , Bayern , and <unk> represent the first , second , and third largest <unk> respectively in the state of Montana . Also in 2011 , <unk> <unk> and <unk> Lake <unk> Company from nearby Lake County opened pub houses at downtown <unk> locations . The city also holds annual the Garden City <unk> and <unk> , and also periodically hosts the Montana Brewers Festival . 
 <unk> 's celebration of the outdoors can also be seen in notable non @-@ profits based in the city such as the Adventure <unk> Association , the <unk> @-@ hunting organizations Boone and <unk> Club and Rocky Mountain Elk Foundation , and the Outdoor Writers Association of America . In an attempt to reduce harmful emissions , the non @-@ profit <unk> in Motion promotes environmentally sustainable transportation options for <unk> , such as walking , <unk> , <unk> , public transportation , and <unk> . Other non @-@ profits headquartered in <unk> illustrate the city 's liberal reputation in Montana . <unk> of marijuana law reform <unk> has its state headquarters in <unk> , as does the Montana <unk> Council . Forward Montana is a " left @-@ leaning though officially <unk> group that seeks to engage young people in politics " . The Montana Justice Foundation , founded in 1979 , is a charitable organization that helps <unk> and <unk> <unk> to access to civil legal aid . The Western Montana Community Center supports the <unk> community and the <unk> Rankin Peace Center focuses on " <unk> , social justice and environmental <unk> " . The largest emergency homeless shelter and soup kitchen in Montana , the <unk> Center , is also located in <unk> . 
 
 = = Sports = = 
 
 <unk> plays host to a variety of intercollegiate , youth , and amateur sports organizations in addition to a Minor league baseball team . The Montana <unk> ' football and basketball teams of the University of Montana have the highest attendance . The Montana <unk> football team has a successful program within the NCAA D @-@ 1 <unk> level . Their home games at Washington – <unk> Stadium have a near 90 % winning percentage and average over 25 @,@ 000 spectators in attendance . All games are televised throughout Montana . The <unk> men 's and Lady <unk> basketball teams have also been successful at the conference level where they both rank at or near the top in attendance , about 4 @,@ 000 and 3 @,@ 000 respectively , and play their home games at <unk> Arena . 
 <unk> is also home to the <unk> <unk> , a rookie affiliate of the Arizona <unk> that plays in the Rocky Mountain @-@ based Pioneer Baseball League . They play their home games at <unk> Park at <unk> Field . Also competing regionally are the <unk> <unk> , a roller derby team that competes at the Adam 's Center . Since 1977 , <unk> has also held " <unk> " , a festival @-@ style rugby tournament hosted by the <unk> <unk> Rugby Club the first weekend in May . The non @-@ elimination tournament focuses on the fun aspect of the game , attracting 36 teams ( male and female ) from around the United States and Canada . In regular season play , the <unk> <unk> compete as part of the Montana Rugby Union alongside another local rugby team , the University of Montana <unk> . 
 
 = = Parks and recreation = = 
 
 The city has over 400 acres ( 160 ha ) of <unk> , 22 miles ( 35 km ) of trails , and nearly 5 @,@ 000 acres ( 2 @,@ 000 ha ) of <unk> open @-@ space . Located at the confluence of three rivers ( the Clark Fork , <unk> , and Blackfoot ) , the area is also popular for white water rafting and , thanks largely to the novel and subsequent film A River <unk> Through It by <unk> native Norman Maclean , is well known for its fly fishing . Additionally , <unk> has two aquatic parks , multiple golf courses , is home to the Adventure <unk> Association , and hosts what <unk> 's World called the " best overall " marathon in the U.S. There are also three <unk> areas within 100 miles ( 160 km ) : Montana <unk> , Discovery <unk> Area , and Lost Trail <unk> Mountain . <unk> farther away are <unk> Pass , <unk> Mountain , and Big Mountain . 
 A system of public parks was developed in <unk> in 1902 with the donation by lumber <unk> Thomas <unk> and his wife <unk> . They gave a 42 @-@ acre ( 17 ha ) tract of land along <unk> Creek for <unk> Park , on the condition that " the land forever be used as a park and for park purposes to which the people of <unk> may . . . find a comfortable , romantic and poetic retreat " . In a follow @-@ up nine years later in a letter to the <unk> , he stressed his interest in having the park remain in as close to a native state as possible . That request , along with the discovery that non @-@ native Norway <unk> were inhibiting the growth of native trees and shrubs such as <unk> , ponderosa pines and Rocky Mountain <unk> , led to the controversial decision to remove Norway <unk> from the park with the hope of returning it to its natural state . 
 In 1924 , <unk> Park was created out of John L. <unk> 's estate near the university . The park today has multiple athletic fields and courts in addition a band shell used by the <unk> City band through the summer . The <unk> club set up a park downtown in 1934 , making <unk> Park the first of a string of parks which line both sides of the Clark Fork River . One of those parks on the southern bank of the river is McCormick Park , which was created with <unk> funds out of surplus highway land , a parcel from the American <unk> and Fur Company , and land donated from the Kate McCormick estate . The 26 @-@ acre ( 11 ha ) park , named for Washington J. McCormick and his wife is home to a skate park , <unk> center , a free bike check @-@ out and a children 's fishing pond . Other popular parks include the <unk> Island <unk> Park , a designated area for dogs to play off @-@ <unk> ; the Montana State veterans ' memorial rose garden ; <unk> Garden , a " living laboratory " garden utilizing water conservation techniques ; and Splash Montana <unk> at <unk> Park . 
 
 = = = <unk> Park = = = 
 
 <unk> Park is located just south of the historic <unk> Theatre downtown . It is located on land reclaimed when the Higgins Avenue Bridge was widened from two lanes to four in 1962 . Before the <unk> , the Clark Fork River divided to create an island with the north channel 's bank extending to nearby buildings such as the <unk> Theatre . The south channel was deepened for the increased water flow and the <unk> land later became <unk> Park . Events in the park were not common until the early 1980s and permanent fixtures like " Out to Lunch " , which began in 1986 . The <unk> Downtown Association took over from Parks and Recreation for management of the park and made improvements to make <unk> Park more event @-@ friendly . <unk> , event circles , brick <unk> , <unk> , and storage structures were added . Large temporary tents were used for events until 1997 when a permanent pavilion was constructed . The park is a hub of city festivities including include " Out to Lunch " , the International Wildlife Film Festival , First Night <unk> , Garden City <unk> and offered intimate concert settings for artists such as <unk> , Chris <unk> , Santana , <unk> Marley , and <unk> King . Located next to <unk> Park is A <unk> for <unk> , a wooden , hand @-@ carved and volunteer @-@ built <unk> ; and Dragon Hollow , a children 's recreational area adjacent to the <unk> . 
 
 = = Government and politics = = 
 
 <unk> 's system of government has changed four times since 1883 when an <unk> form of government was approved with the town charter . The city adopted a commission @-@ council form of government in 1911 with the opening of new City Hall and a council – manager government in 1954 before returning to an <unk> form of government in 1959 . Since January 1 , 1997 , <unk> has been governed in accordance with the <unk> City Charter , which calls for a mayor @-@ council system of government . 
 The current system comprises a mayor and city treasurer elected in a <unk> vote and twelve city council members who must reside in and are elected from one of six wards with each ward having two council members . All positions are nominally <unk> . Council members and the mayor are elected to four @-@ year terms with council @-@ member elections being <unk> to allow only one member from each ward to up for re @-@ election . There are no term limits for either position . 
 <unk> 's state legislative delegation is the second largest in the Montana Legislature and is represented by districts 91 – 100 in the Montana House of Representatives and districts 46 – 50 in the Montana Senate . Having thirteen Democrats and two Republicans in its state legislative delegation , <unk> is known as a more liberal area than the rest of the state . 
 Though <unk> 's political <unk> may not be unique for a college town , its initiative to make marijuana possession the lowest priority of law enforcement in 2006 , and symbolic resolutions calling on Congress to withdraw from Iraq in 2007 , and to amend the U.S. Constitution to declare that " corporations are not human beings " in 2011 , often put it at odds with the rest of the state . In 2011 , the Montana legislature , with a Republican House majority , attempted to <unk> <unk> 's marijuana law and <unk> its ability to have an anti @-@ discrimination ordinance that included the <unk> community . The marijuana repeal was vetoed by then – Governor Brian <unk> and the attempt to repeal the other died in the Senate . 
 
 = = Education = = 
 
 <unk> 's first school was opened in late 1869 with sixteen students from around the region and their teacher Emma C. <unk> who had come to <unk> via a two @-@ month trip by horseback , railroad , and boat from Baltimore at the invitation of her brother . She resigned two years later upon marrying William H. H. Dickinson ( the first couple married in <unk> ) and was replaced by Elizabeth <unk> who later married <unk> 's first mayor , Frank H. Woody . The first public high school was opened in 1904 but was converted back to a grade school after the A. J. Gibson @-@ designed <unk> County High School ( now <unk> High School ) was opened in 1908 . After several expansions , Stanford University was commissioned in 1951 to create a master building plan to manage future growth . It suggested purchasing land and building an additional campus at the Garden City Airport 's Hale Field , which was gradually being replaced by the <unk> County Airport , which was then southwest of town . The new school ( now Sentinel High School ) was opened in 1957 . Initially the two campuses were separated between upper and lower <unk> with upper <unk> in the new school , but in 1965 , the two campuses became separate high schools . In 1974 , the private Loyola Sacred Heart Catholic High School was created from a merger of the all @-@ girls Sacred Heart Academy ( est . 1873 ) and the all @-@ boys Loyola High School ( est . 1912 ) . In 1980 , <unk> 's third public high school , Big Sky , was established . 
 <unk> 's public schools are part of the <unk> County Public School districts 1 , 4 , 20 , and 23 . In <unk> , there are nine public elementary schools ( kindergarten to 5th grade ) , three public middle schools ( 6th to 8th grades ) , four public high schools ( 9th to 12th grades ) , and three public schools serving kindergarten to 8th grade . <unk> also has several private schools including an international school , religious @-@ affiliated schools , as well as Next <unk> <unk> , a theater academy high school operated by the <unk> Children 's Theatre . 
 The University of Montana dominates higher education in <unk> . The university , established in 1893 , was Montana 's first , and has the state 's second @-@ largest enrollment , with 12 @,@ 922 students as of 2015 ) . The campus houses six colleges and three schools including Montana 's first and only law school , the Alexander <unk> III School of Law at the University of Montana . The university is also the location of the state 's Regional Federal <unk> Library , and houses the state <unk> . The University of Montana College of Technology , established in 1956 and formerly known as the <unk> <unk> Technical Center , offers fast @-@ track learning programs . Multiple vocational programs not affiliated with the university ranging from photography and <unk> to truck driving also have a presence in <unk> . 
 
 = = Media = = 
 
 
 = = = Broadcast = = = 
 
 <unk> 's single – broadcast over – air television media market is the largest in Montana and ranked 165 nationally in as of 2015 . Though <unk> itself is second in population to <unk> , Montana , <unk> 's single @-@ broadcast over @-@ air television media market includes all of <unk> , <unk> , <unk> , Mineral , Lake , <unk> , and Sanders Counties in the more densely populated western region of Montana and serves over 112 @,@ 600 television homes as of 2015 . <unk> is home to three local affiliate channels : <unk> @-@ TV ( CBS / <unk> , The CW ; founded 1970 ; channel 8 ) , <unk> @-@ TV ( NBC ; founded 1954 as <unk> @-@ TV ; channel 13 , and <unk> @-@ TV ( ABC , <unk> ; founded 1991 ; channel 23 ) . Also based in <unk> at the University of Montana is Montana PBS ( founded 1984 ; channel 11 ) . There are seventeen FM radio stations and four AM radio stations licensed in the city . 
 
 = = = Print = = = 
 
 <unk> has four main sources of print media : the <unk> ( primary daily ) , <unk> Independent ( alternative weekly ) , Montana <unk> ( college ) , and New West ( digital , progressive ) . The <unk> was founded as a weekly publication in 1870 as The <unk> and Cedar Creek Pioneer . As of 2015 , the <unk> remains <unk> 's most popular newspaper with a circulation of over 26 @,@ 000 , making it the third most read daily newspaper in Montana behind the <unk> Gazette and the Great Falls Tribune . The <unk> Independent ( founded 1991 ) is the largest weekly newspaper in Montana and the states only member of the Association of Alternative <unk> . With over 21 @,@ 000 readers it has twice the circulation of second place <unk> <unk> . The newspaper is distributed free to more than 600 locations across Western Montana from Hamilton in the south to <unk> in the north . The Montana <unk> ( founded 1891 ) is likewise distributed free throughout parts of <unk> with heavy student traffic from the University of Montana where the newspaper is printed Monday through Friday during the school year . New West was founded in 2005 as a left @-@ leaning " next @-@ generation media company " that focused on culture , environment , economy , and politics in the Rocky Mountain West . 
 
 = = Infrastructure = = 
 
 
 = = = Health care = = = 
 
 <unk> has two primary health care facilities : St. Patrick Hospital and Health Sciences Center and Community Medical Center . St. Patrick 's was founded in 1873 under the sponsorship of the Sisters of Providence . It is the only Level II trauma center in the region , the largest medical facility in Western Montana , and has undergone three major expansions since the 1980s . The hospital has 195 acute @-@ care beds , and admitted over 9 @,@ 700 patients in 2003 . The name was changed from " St. Patrick Hospital " to " St. Patrick Hospital and Health Sciences Center " in 2000 to reflect an increasing involvement with national medical research and education . The Community Medical Center and its adjacent medical facilities are located near Fort <unk> and is part of a modern complex that includes a nursing home , the <unk> <unk> Children 's Center , and private offices . It was founded in 1922 as <unk> Hospital by doctors Will <unk> and Charles <unk> and has been at its current location since 1972 . It is the only facility providing <unk> and newborn care in <unk> County and the only hospital in Western Montana with a separate <unk> <unk> Care Unit . The center is partnered with Seattle Children 's Hospital . The nearest Level I trauma center to <unk> is <unk> Medical Center in Seattle , Washington . 
 
 = = = Utilities = = = 
 
 The earliest <unk> drew their water directly from the Clark Fork River or nearby <unk> Creek . The first water system consisted of a Native American known as One @-@ Eyed Riley and his friend filling buckets of water from the <unk> Creek and <unk> them door to door on a <unk> cart . In 1871 city co @-@ founder Frank <unk> began construction of a log pipe and wooden main system that flowed from the <unk> Creek 2 @.@ 5 miles ( 4 km ) north of the city . With the addition of two small covered reservoirs , the first municipal water system was begun in 1880 . With an intake dam built in 1901 with a settling basin capacity of 3 million US gallons ( 11 @,@ 000 m3 ) , the <unk> Creek continued to meet demands of the city until 1935 when five wells were added to respond to increased summer and fall demand . This system is still maintained as an emergency backup , but was discontinued as a primary source after <unk> outbreak in 1983 . Since then , <unk> has relied on the <unk> Valley <unk> as the sole source of water . In 1889 , the first electrical plant was built by A. B. Hammond to power his major downtown properties such as the <unk> <unk> and the Florence Hotel . In 1905 , the <unk> <unk> ( by then owned by <unk> King William A. Clark purchased the water system and consolidated it with its vast electrical holdings to create the <unk> Light and Water Company ( ML & W ) a year later . Electricity and water remained <unk> after ML & W 's sale to the Montana Power Company ( MPC ) in 1929 . In 1979 , MPC sold its water utility holdings as Mountain Water Company to Park Water Company in <unk> , California , which since 2011 has been a subsidiary of The Carlyle Group . In 2015 , the City of <unk> was legally granted its " ' right to acquire ' the water system by exercising its power of eminent domain " , but as of June 2015 , that decision is under appeal . 
 Following the <unk> of Montana 's electricity market in 1997 , Montana Power Company began to <unk> its energy business . MPC sold substantially all its electrical generating assets to the PPL Corporation in December 1997 and its energy transmission and distribution business to <unk> Corporation in February 2002 . Despite filing for bankruptcy in 2002 , <unk> Corporation 's subsidiary <unk> Energy is the primary provider of electric and natural gas service to <unk> in addition to the Rural Utilities Service 's <unk> Electric Cooperative . 
 Local telephone service in the area is provided by <unk> and Blackfoot <unk> . Major cell phone providers include AT & T , <unk> , Verizon , and T @-@ Mobile . <unk> collection in <unk> is handled by Allied Waste Industries and Grant Creek Water Systems . Allied Waste also handles recycling through a program where customers can purchase special blue bags to designate <unk> . <unk> has also been offered by <unk> Valley <unk> since 1992 , by Garden City <unk> since 2010 which offers <unk> <unk> , and by Pacific Steel & <unk> which offers drop @-@ off recycling . <unk> service is handled by the City of <unk> <unk> Division . 
 
 = = = City layout and development = = = 
 
 In the mid @-@ 1860s , C. P. Higgins and Frank <unk> began plotting what would become the town of <unk> along the <unk> Military Road , which ran parallel to the Clark Fork River . Through downtown <unk> , the route of the road is now Front Street . It is intersected by Higgins Avenue , to which a bridge across the Clark Fork was added in 1873 . The intersection of these two streets became the default center of the city , and remains the numerical center regarding city street addresses . The arrival of the Northern Pacific Railway in 1883 led to a housing boom along the tracks , particularly on the northern side where many of the railway workers would reside . When the Higgins Avenue Bridge was replaced in 1893 , they debated whether the bridge should continue southwest toward the <unk> Valley as it had earlier , or due south . <unk> W. M. <unk> and W. J. Stephens had already laid out plots of land five years earlier for what they hoped would be a new town of " South <unk> " . The streets there were perpendicular to the <unk> <unk> Road while Judge <unk> Knowles who owned the land just south of the river preferred the north @-@ south plan and did not want to become part of South <unk> . The result was a 7 × 14 – block area along the west side of Higgins Avenue commonly referred to as the Slant Streets centered along what is now Stephens Avenue . Stephens Avenue and Brooks Street are the only <unk> to traverse the city <unk> along with the <unk> Branch of Montana Rail Link . The rest of the city , with the exception of Downtown , where streets follow the angle of the river , and newer expansions into the hills , strictly follow the grid plan . With the establishment of the University of Montana in 1893 and the announcement that the now @-@ defunct Milwaukee Road would be located south of the river , houses began to spread quickly throughout the university and south side districts . The area near the university was promoted as high @-@ end and luxurious homes appeare