 = <unk> Line = 
 
 The <unk> Line ( Norwegian : <unk> ) is a 9 @.@ 5 @-@ kilometre ( 5 @.@ 9 mi ) railway line between <unk> and <unk> in Norway . The line runs along the same corridor as the <unk> Line , offering increased capacity , speed and <unk> on the rail network west of Oslo . The first part opened in 2005 , and in 2011 an extension opened from <unk> to <unk> . An extension to <unk> in Oslo will perhaps be built after <unk> . Most of the railway is in tunnel and is <unk> for 160 km / h ( 99 mph ) running . The entire railway is electrified at 15 <unk> 16 2 ⁄ 3 Hz AC . The first section cost NOK 3 @.@ 7 billion , while the second is budgeted at NOK 2 @.@ 7 billion . 
 The purpose of the new line is to allow regional and express trains to run directly between <unk> Station , <unk> Station and <unk> Station , without being slowed and delayed by commuter trains that make frequent stops at intermediate stations . The <unk> Line will improve <unk> , and capacity will increase from 12 to 26 trains per hour in each direction . Travel time from <unk> to <unk> Station will be reduced from 20 to 13 minutes . The line has received criticism for not being a true high @-@ speed line , and for <unk> Station not being in compliance with accessibility requirements . Similar parallel , high @-@ speed lines have been or will be built northeast and southeast of Oslo . 
 The line is built , owned and maintained by the Norwegian National Rail Administration . At <unk> , the line connects to the <unk> Line , which runs to Oslo Central Station in the east . At <unk> , the line connects to the <unk> and <unk> Lines ; the latter connects to the <unk> and <unk> Line at <unk> . The line is served by Norwegian State Railways with regional trains to <unk> , <unk> and <unk> , and the express trains along the <unk> Line and the Bergen Line ; in addition , the Airport Express Train operates from <unk> to Oslo Airport , Gardermoen . During night , freight trains also use the line . 
 
 = = Background = = 
 
 Following the construction of the high @-@ speed Gardermoen Line from Oslo , via Oslo Airport , Gardermoen , to <unk> , the Norwegian Ministry of Transport and Communications started planning additional high @-@ speed lines west and southeast of Oslo . The <unk> and <unk> Lines would allow express and regional trains to travel faster and more reliably to <unk> and <unk> , leaving the old tracks for slower freight trains , and commuter trains making frequent stops . Construction of the <unk> Line will , at the earliest , be completed in 2015 . 
 The Gardermoen Line had shown that profits could be made by operating passenger trains , but that it would not be possible to debt @-@ finance short @-@ distance tracks in Eastern Norway . Therefore , a conventional financial method for the <unk> Line was started . While the railway is entirely financed through allocation through the state budget , the <unk> was secured through a political compromise for investments in Greater Oslo , the Oslo <unk> 2 . <unk> of a diverse range of road and public transport investments — including new <unk> , extension of the Oslo Metro and new railways — would be made through a " package " . This involved both state , county and toll funding being collected in one lot , and then <unk> the funds to the agencies responsible for the investments . 
 Prior to the construction , the Western Corridor had a capacity of 12 – 14 trains per hour in each direction west of <unk> . The first section of the <unk> Line , from <unk> to <unk> , increased the capacity with an additional two trains . The opening of <unk> Station will increase capacity with four more , since all stations along the line between Oslo and <unk> will then have four platforms . When the whole line is completed , total capacity in the Western Corridor will be 26 trains per hour . This is equivalent to 5 @,@ 500 cars per hour , and exceeds the capacity of a four @-@ lane motorway . 
 The <unk> Line is also a necessary component to allow a high @-@ speed route to be built along the <unk> and <unk> Lines . The former is planned to branch off at <unk> , while the latter would branch of at <unk> , and become a 60 @-@ kilometre ( 37 mi ) <unk> of the Bergen Line . The first sections of the upgraded <unk> Line opened in 1995 and 2001 , and additional proposals are under planning for the remaining sections . 
 
