 = <unk> = 
 
 <unk> is a fungal genus in the family <unk> . The genus is monotypic , containing the single species <unk> <unk> . It is an earthstar , so named because the spore @-@ bearing <unk> 's outer wall splits open into the shape of a star . The inedible fungus has a cosmopolitan distribution , and has been found in Africa , Asia , North and South America , and Europe , where it grows in <unk> @-@ rich forests or in woodlands , especially on well @-@ drained and sandy soils . A somewhat rare fungus , it appears on the Red <unk> of 12 European countries , and in 2004 it was one of 33 species proposed for protection under the Bern Convention by the European Council for Conservation of Fungi . 
 The fruit body , initially shaped like a puffball , is <unk> within an outer covering that splits open from the top to form rays . These rays curve down to expose an inner <unk> spore case , which contains the fertile spore @-@ bearing tissue , the gleba . The fungus is unique among the earthstars in having a spore case that is supported by multiple stalks , and is <unk> by several small holes <unk> of its common names salt @-@ <unk> earthstar and <unk> . It is the largest of the earthstar fungi , and reaches diameters of up to 12 cm ( 4 @.@ 7 in ) . Its spherical spores have elongated warts that create a ridge @-@ like pattern on their surface . The spores are dispersed when falling water hits the outer wall of the spore sac , creating <unk> of air that force the spores through the holes . 
 
 = = Taxonomy and phylogeny = = 
 
 The species was first mentioned in the scientific literature by Samuel <unk> in the second edition of John Ray 's Synopsis <unk> <unk> <unk> in <unk> . <unk> briefly described the mushroom like so : " fungus <unk> coli <unk> <unk> , cum volva <unk> " ( mushroom dusty , like a <unk> <unk> , volva star @-@ shaped ) , and went on to explain that he found it in <unk> in Kent . 
 It was first described scientifically as a new species in 1776 from collections made in England by James Dickson , who named it <unk> <unk> . He found it growing in roadside banks and <unk> among <unk> in Suffolk and Norfolk . <unk> Auguste <unk> first defined and published the new genus <unk> in 1809 , with the species renamed <unk> <unk> ( an illegitimate renaming ) . Christian <unk> Persoon had previously placed the species in Geastrum in 1801 , while Samuel Frederick Gray would in 1821 describe the genus <unk> for it . <unk> <unk> received its current and final name when August Carl Joseph <unk> moved Dickson 's name to <unk> in 1842 , replacing <unk> 's name . 
 In North America the fungus began to be reported in the late 19th century , first from Colorado by Charles Horton Peck , and later from Florida , collected by <unk> Underwood in 1891 ; both findings were reported by Andrew Price Morgan in April 1892 . In 1897 , <unk> <unk> Cook also reported having collected it the year before from " <unk> Beach " . Curtis Gates Lloyd described <unk> <unk> from a South African specimen in 1919 , but in 1942 , William Henry Long examined that specimen and concluded that it was a weathered spore sac of M. <unk> that had become detached from the outer star @-@ shaped exoperidium . This conclusion was confirmed in a later study of the material . 
 <unk> had been classified in the <unk> family until 1973 , when British mycologist Donald <unk> placed it in the <unk> based on the presence of <unk> ( stout columns that extend from the peridium to the central core of the fruit body ) in the gleba , and the absence of a true hymenium . In his 1989 <unk> , <unk> <unk> returned it to the <unk> . Molecular analysis of DNA sequences has confirmed the traditional belief that <unk> and Geastrum are closely related . 
 <unk> Jan <unk> proposed a variety <unk> in 1958 , which has been sunk back into <unk> with the species . M. <unk> is the sole species in <unk> , making the genus monotypic . Because the original type material has been lost , in 1989 <unk> suggested that Dickson 's illustration in his 1776 publication ( <unk> . III : <unk> & b ) be used as the <unk> . 
 The specific epithet is derived from the Latin words <unk> , meaning " <unk> " , and <unk> , meaning " shape " — Berkeley 's vernacular name " <unk> puff @-@ ball " also refers to a <unk> . Gray called it the " <unk> pill @-@ box " . The generic name is from the Greek words <unk> , meaning " countless " and <unk> , meaning " mouth " ( the source of the technical term <unk> ) . The species is commonly known as the " salt @-@ and @-@ <unk> <unk> earthstar " or simply the " <unk> " . 
 
 = = Description = = 
 
 The fruit bodies start their development underground or buried in leaf debris , linked to a <unk> of mycelium at the base . As they mature , the exoperidium ( the outer tissue layer of the peridium ) splits open into 7 to 14 rays which curve backward ; this pushes the fruit body above the substrate . Fully opened specimens can reach dimensions of 2 – 12 cm ( 0 @.@ 8 – 4 @.@ 7 in ) from ray tip to tip . The rays are of <unk> size , with tips that often roll back inward . They comprise three distinct layers of tissue . The inner <unk> layer ( so named for the resemblance to the tightly packed cells of plant <unk> ) is <unk> and thick when fresh , and initially pale beige but darkening to yellow or brown as it matures , often <unk> and <unk> off in the process . The exterior mycelial layer , often matted with fine leaf debris or dirt , usually cracks to reveal a middle fibrous layer , which is made of densely packed hyphae 1 – 2 @.@ 5 μm wide . The base of the fruit body is <unk> to vaulted in shape , and often covered with adhering dirt . The roughly spherical spore sac ( <unk> ) measures 1 – 5 cm ( 0 @.@ 4 – 2 @.@ 0 in ) in diameter , and is supported by a cluster of short columns shaped like flattened spheres . It is gray @-@ brown in color , and <unk> <unk> with small , lightly interconnected warts . There are several to many evenly dispersed mouths , the <unk> , mainly on the upper half of the <unk> . They are roughly circular with <unk> ( fringed ) edges . The inedible fruit bodies have no distinct taste , although dried specimens develop an odor resembling <unk> powder or <unk> <unk> . 
 Like many earthstars , the fungus uses the force of falling <unk> to help disperse the spores , which are ejected in little bursts when objects ( such as rain ) strike the outer wall of the spore sac . The gleba is brown to grayish @-@ brown , with a cotton @-@ like texture that , when compressed , allows the <unk> to <unk> quickly and create a puff of air that is forced out through the <unk> . This generates a cloud of spores that can then be carried by the wind . There are <unk> ( sterile structures that start at the base of the gleba and extend through it ) , which are usually not evident in the mature gleba , but apparent at the base of the spore sac . The <unk> are not connected to the <unk> , but rather , terminate within the gleba at some distance from them . The capillitia ( sterile strands within the gleba ) are long , slender , free , <unk> , <unk> , and 2 – 5 μm thick , with thickened walls . The spores are spherical , <unk> , and are ornamented with irregularly shaped <unk> <unk> up to 2 μm high . They measure 3 @.@ 9 – 4 @.@ 8 μm in diameter ( without ornamentation ) , and 5 @.@ 4 – 7 @.@ 0 μm including the ornamentation . 
 
 = = = Similar species = = = 
 
 <unk> <unk> is a distinctive species easily characterized by its size — being the largest earthstar fungus — as well as the multiple openings on its spore <unk> and stalk supporting the <unk> . Historically , it was thought that the holes might have been a result of insects . This was discussed and rejected by Thomas <unk> Woodward in 1797 : 
 It has been doubted whether these mouths might not be accidental , and formed by insects after the expansion of the plant . But this ( not to mention their <unk> , and that each is <unk> by its border of <unk> ) is clearly <unk> , from the marks of the projections formed by the mouths being seen on the expanded rays , when <unk> opened ... I have likewise found an abortive plant , in which the seed did not <unk> ; but which had numerous projecting papillae on the head , where the mouths should have been formed . 
 
 = = Habitat and distribution = = 
 
 <unk> is saprobic , deriving nutrients from decomposing organic matter . Fruit bodies grow grouped in well @-@ drained or sandy soil , often in the partial shade of trees . The species occurs in deciduous forests and mixed forests , gardens , along <unk> and grassy road banks , and grazed grasslands . In the Northern Hemisphere , it tends to grow on well @-@ drained south @-@ facing slopes , while it prefers a similar habitat on north @-@ facing slopes in Australia . In Europe , its major habitat is riparian mixed forests dominated by <unk> <unk> and <unk> <unk> along the great rivers . In Hawaii , it has been collected at elevations above 2 @,@ 000 m ( 6 @,@ 600 ft ) where it appears to favor the <unk> ( <unk> <unk> ) forest . 
 The species is widespread , being known in its natural habitat from all five continents , but is not found in abundance . <unk> <unk> is rare in Europe , where it appears on the Regional Red <unk> of 12 countries , and is one of 33 candidate species for listing in <unk> I of the Convention on the Conservation of European Wildlife and Natural <unk> ( the " Bern Convention " ) . Although originally described from England , it was considered extinct in mainland Britain until it was found again in Suffolk in 2006 near Ipswich , one of its original localities — it had been last reported in the country in 1880 . The fungus is considered extinct in Switzerland . Its most northerly location is southern Sweden , although it is generally rare in northern Europe . It is similarly widespread but rarely encountered in North America , although there may be isolated localities , like New Mexico , where it is more abundant . In Australia , where its range is limited to the central New South Wales coast , it may have been introduced from exotic plant material . 
 
 
