 = = = <unk> and <unk> = = = 
 
 In general , three different types of sounds are produced by <unk> ( and other <unk> <unk> ) . These are click trains , which are made of numerous individual <unk> , usually <unk> signals that change from low value to high value quickly , burst pulses , which are individual <unk> with high repetition and can be heard by humans only as a <unk> sound , and whistles , which are signals that are pure @-@ tones and whose frequency varies depending on the time . <unk> <unk> produce all three sounds , but most commonly make burst pulses . <unk> is more common when <unk> <unk> <unk> with other <unk> species such as common <unk> . Their <unk> signals are <unk> and of short duration , much like those other whistle @-@ producing <unk> <unk> . They tend to have <unk> frequency spectra which peak between 40 and 50 kHz at low frequency and between 80 and 110 kHz at high frequency . The species ' <unk> signals are about 9 – 12 <unk> lower than for the larger white @-@ <unk> <unk> . 
 
 = = = <unk> and predation = = = 
 
 <unk> <unk> prey consume a variety of fish and <unk> species . Common fish species eaten include <unk> , lantern fish , <unk> , <unk> , <unk> , horse <unk> , <unk> and red <unk> . They are generally coordinated hunters . Their very flexible foraging strategies can change depending on the environment . In certain parts of New Zealand , where deep oceanic waters meet the shore , <unk> <unk> forage in deep scattering layers at night . They arrive at the hunting site individually , but form groups when in the layer . The <unk> use their <unk> to detect and isolate an individual prey . Groups of foraging <unk> tend to increase when the layer is near the surface and decrease when it descends . 
 When hunting in shallower waters in New Zealand and Argentina , <unk> <unk> tend to forage during the day . The <unk> chase schools of fish or <unk> and herd them into stationary balls . They may control the school with light reflected from their white <unk> . Dolphins herd prey against the surface , but also horizontally against the shore , a point of land , or the hull of a boat . During these times , <unk> <unk> are believed to increase prey availability for other predators , including other <unk> , <unk> , sharks , and <unk> . In Argentina , <unk> <unk> may use bird <unk> to locate and herd prey . Conversely , <unk> and sharks take advantage of the <unk> hunts . <unk> <unk> are themselves preyed on by killer <unk> and large sharks . Dolphins avoid killer <unk> by swimming into shallower water . <unk> <unk> are also susceptible to <unk> by certain nematode , <unk> , and <unk> species , mostly the genera <unk> and <unk> , and <unk> <unk> , <unk> <unk> , and <unk> <unk> . 
 
 = = = Social behaviour and reproduction = = = 
 
 <unk> <unk> live in a fission @-@ fusion society , with most group size increases occurring during foraging and decreases in group sizes occurring during resting and traveling . In the <unk> San José off the <unk> Peninsula , <unk> commonly switch between small traveling groups and large <unk> groups , and encounter a variety of associates . Studies of <unk> off <unk> , New Zealand , showed the <unk> normally live in large groups that split into smaller <unk> . These <unk> are composed of mating adults ( mating groups ) , mothers with calves ( nursery groups ) and <unk> adults . <unk> <unk> have a <unk> mating system in which both males and females mate with multiple partners . Mating groups are generally made of around 10 males and a single female . These mating groups can be found in both shallow and deep water but more often gather near shore . 
 In the mating groups , the males pursue a female in high @-@ speed chases . Females seem to prefer males with great speed and agility rather than size , strength , or aggression . Females may extend the chase as long as possible so only the best male remains . Females may try to evade males that are not vigorous or lack social skill . Males also may form <unk> to catch females . Unlike male <unk> <unk> , male <unk> <unk> cannot <unk> females . The time when female <unk> <unk> first reproduce varies between regions . New Zealand <unk> first reproduce at about seven to years , with possibly six to seven years for Argentine <unk> . A study of <unk> <unk> off the coast of Peru showed the reproductive cycle lasts around 28 @.@ 6 months , with mother <unk> pregnant for 12 @.@ 9 months , <unk> for a further 12 months , and resting for 3 @.@ 7 months before the cycle begins again . During copulation , females tend to be on the top . As with all species where females mate with multiple partners , male <unk> <unk> have large <unk> for sperm competition . <unk> <unk> sometimes engage in sexual behaviour for reasons other than reproduction , perhaps for <unk> , communication , or strengthening social bonds . <unk> behaviour between males has been observed . Dolphins having sex for social reasons tend to be more relaxed . 
 Females with calves tend to gather in nursery groups in shallow water . Nursery groups likely provide mothers and calves more time to rest , which is important for both . While the <unk> of nursery groups vary by month , resting is the predominant behaviour during most months . The formation of nursery groups in shallow waters also allows members to hunt prey species that inhabit in these waters . Both adults and calves have been observed to chase and catch fish , and the adults may be teaching the calves how to hunt . In contrast to shallower waters , hunting in deep water at night may be too dangerous for calves . <unk> are particularly vulnerable to predators like killer <unk> and use of shallow water by nursery groups may be a way to avoid predation . Nursery groups tend to avoid mating groups . Adult males in these groups will aggressively herd and chase females . They can separate calves from their mothers and harass them , as well . <unk> may also become even more vulnerable to predators as they become exhausted and <unk> . Mother <unk> may look after calves that are not their own . 
 
 = = = Aerial behaviour = = = 
 
 <unk> <unk> perform a number of aerial displays , including <unk> , <unk> , <unk> , <unk> , spins , and <unk> . They also perform head @-@ over @-@ tail <unk> which have been called the most " <unk> " of the displays . A <unk> re @-@ entry is performed when a <unk> <unk> entirely water and positions its back in a curve while it <unk> the tail to land back in the water head @-@ first . " <unk> " is similar , except the snout and tail remain in the water when the <unk> is the arch . <unk> , head @-@ over @-@ tail <unk> , <unk> , <unk> , <unk> , and spins are often done over and over again . Young <unk> <unk> apparently are not born with the ability to perform the <unk> and must learn to master each one . <unk> appear to learn the <unk> in this order : noisy <unk> , head first re @-@ entries , coordinated <unk> , and <unk> <unk> . Adults may perform different <unk> in different contexts , and calves may independently learn how to perform <unk> , but learn when to perform these when interacting others . 
 
 = = Relationship with humans = = 
 
 
 = = = Status = = = 
 
 The <unk> <unk> , protected in much of its range , is listed as Data <unk> by the IUCN because ; " ... assessment of global population status is not possible with the currently available estimates of abundance and <unk> . The <unk> off Peru has probably been <unk> , but present data do not allow <unk> of present decline " . <unk> <unk> may fall victim to the small <unk> fisheries of Peru and Chile . The expansion of these fisheries could have started in Peru when the <unk> fishery collapsed in 1972 . Dolphins have also been caught in gill nets in New Zealand , but catches appear to have dropped since the 1970s and 1980s . In Peru , <unk> <unk> are killed in large numbers ( 10 @.@ 000 @-@ 15 @.@ 000 per year ) and used as shark bait or for human consumption . The <unk> are also thought to have been <unk> off South Africa , but the numbers are not considered large . 
 The <unk> <unk> is listed on <unk> II of the Convention on the Conservation of <unk> Species of Wild Animals ( <unk> ) as it has an <unk> conservation status or would benefit significantly from international co @-@ operation organised by tailored agreements . 
 
 = = = <unk> farming = = = 
 
 The effect of <unk> farming on <unk> <unk> has been studied in Admiralty Bay , New Zealand . <unk> <unk> are commonly seen in this area , which is also where the greatest density of farming activity is proposed . Apparently , <unk> rarely enter existing farms , and when they do , they usually swim quickly up the lanes and between rows of lines and floats . 
 
 = = = Tourism = = = 
 
 <unk> <unk> are popular attractions for whale @-@ watching tours . Since 1997 , <unk> @-@ watching activities have increased in <unk> , with <unk> <unk> ( along with <unk> 's <unk> ) as the target species . <unk> interested in seeing <unk> <unk> grew from 1 @,@ 393 in 1997 to 1 @,@ 840 in 2000 . <unk> with <unk> increased from 25 % during 1999 to 90 % in 2001 . <unk> watching in this areas started as an alternative to whale watching , which was mostly based on that of the southern right whale . <unk> <unk> watching is also popular in New Zealand , whose <unk> @-@ watching industry begin in the late 1980s , as a side attraction to sperm whale watching . <unk> and <unk> watching tours have grown with around 75 permitted <unk> tour operators . New Zealand has several locations to view and swim with <unk> <unk> , notably in <unk> and Marlborough Sounds . 
 While <unk> <unk> tourism is a larger industry in New Zealand than it is in Argentina , the effects of tourism on the <unk> seem to be lower in the former than the latter . New Zealand tours are operated under permits , and are limited in number and have conditions and guidelines related to approach procedures and swim operations . By contrast , no direct regulation of <unk> watching is done in Argentina . As such , <unk> activities are often disturbed by touring vessels . 
 
