 Alien <unk> has a minimal plot . The story follows the <unk> , a spider from the planet <unk> , who has crash @-@ landed on Earth during an attempt to rescue a lady spider , <unk> . <unk> must locate <unk> and collect pieces of his spacecraft in order to return to <unk> . 
 
 = = Development = = 
 
 On 8 November 2011 , the game was announced in a press release , with <unk> Software Productions as the developer and <unk> Media as the publisher . The press release indicated that the game would be released in the second quarter of 2012 . 
 Alien <unk> was advertised as a PlayStation Vita game early in its development history , with Sony using gameplay footage of the game on the Vita at a presentation at Gamescom 2011 . The game was never released on that platform , however . In an interview , <unk> Software CEO Daniel <unk> claimed that the game was developed for all major platforms , and after bringing <unk> Media on board as a publisher , the latter chose which platforms to release the game on , and when . The project manager at <unk> Media for Alien <unk> , Andrew <unk> , noted that the developer attempted to secure a publisher by pitching the game on a large number of platforms . In a separate interview with Daniel <unk> , conducted in October 2012 , <unk> Software 's CEO called the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 the game 's lead platforms , stating that the game was " designed to be played with a <unk> " . 
 It took eight months for <unk> to build the physics behind the web @-@ based <unk> and swing game mechanic . During early builds of the game , the motion was slower , but the development team <unk> up the movement , feeling it was <unk> to the character . The Sonic the Hedgehog series served as an inspiration for the game 's pace . Significant effort was put into creating the game 's visual style and making <unk> a relatable , charismatic character . Daniel <unk> cited <unk> , <unk> , and <unk> as influences for the game 's aesthetics . Comics and cartoons served as influences for <unk> 's design . The character was given a pair of large yellow eyes , which allowed the character to <unk> . Two of the legs were removed , bringing the total from eight to six , which Andrew <unk> described as an effort to avoid triggering the fears of people with <unk> and " make the character a little more friendly looking and little less creepy " . It was only after making these changes to <unk> that the developers decided to make <unk> an extraterrestrial , as that would justify the character design 's deviations from regular spiders . 
 The game was delayed several times . In August 2012 , the website <unk> Fans reported that the game would be delayed into the fall of that year . By October , a preview on the gaming website <unk> listed the release date as 31 December 2012 . The game was released on the Xbox 360 , Microsoft Windows , and Macintosh on 20 March 2013 , and was released on the PlayStation 3 on 8 May 2013 . 
 
 = = Reception = = 
 
 Alien <unk> received mixed to negative reviews upon release . At Metacritic , a video game review aggregator , the Xbox 360 version of the game received an average score of 55 out of 100 , based on 19 reviews . 
 The game 's visuals were praised by reviewers . GamesRadar 's Lorenzo <unk> opined that " <unk> characters , beautiful visuals , and upbeat music stand out as the high points of Alien <unk> " . A large number of reviewers called the game and its characters " cute " . While a few of the reviewers praised the game 's music , Jeremy <unk> of Hardcore Gamer found that it lacked staying power . He noted , however , that the music could be muted without also <unk> the sound effects , allowing people to play their own music . 
 Critics near universally took issue with the game 's controls . Critics found that the <unk> that they shot did not go where they wanted them to go , and multiple reviewers described navigation as " trial and error " . Reviewers also found that they could not always jump when they wanted to , and one reviewer found that power @-@ ups failed to activate when she wanted them to . Reviewers also complained that it was extremely difficult to get enough stars to progress from one stage to the next , forcing players to replay the same levels over and over again . Because points are <unk> each time <unk> dies , the problems with the control scheme <unk> how difficult it is to get enough stars to progress . 
 Opinions on the game 's mid @-@ level <unk> system were mixed . Matt Cullen of Canadian Online Gaming noted that the checkpoints meant that players were not sent too far back into the level after each death , saving time . Official Xbox Magazine 's Taylor <unk> , however , noted that the checkpoints save players ' point progress , meaning that players would have to start the level over if their performance wasn 't good enough before they reached the <unk> . 
 
 
 = Australian <unk> = 
 
 The Australian <unk> ( <unk> <unk> ) is a <unk> bird in the genus <unk> native to much of southern and northeastern Australia . Measuring 46 – 53 centimetres ( 18 – 21 in ) in length , it has all @-@ black plumage , beak and mouth , as well as strong grey @-@ black legs and feet . The upperparts are glossy , with a purple , blue or green <unk> , and its black feathers have grey bases . The Australian <unk> is distinguished from the Australian <unk> species by its throat <unk> , which are prominent in adult birds . Older adult individuals have white irises , younger adults have a white irises with an inner blue rim , while younger birds have dark brown irises until fifteen months of age , and <unk> irises with an inner blue rim around each pupil until age two years and ten months . Nicholas <unk> <unk> and Thomas <unk> described the Australian <unk> in 1827 , its species name highlighting its similarity with the <unk> <unk> ( C. <unk> ) . Two subspecies are recognised , which differ slightly in calls and are quite <unk> genetically . 
 The preferred habitat is open woodland and transitional zones . It has adapted well to urban environments and is a common city bird in Sydney , Canberra and Perth . An omnivorous and opportunistic <unk> , it eats a wide variety of plant and animal material , as well as food waste from urban areas . In eastern Australia its range is strongly correlated with the presence of sheep , and it has been blamed for killing lambs . However , this is very rare , and the <unk> most often <unk> for <unk> and stillborn animals as well as newborn lamb <unk> . The Australian <unk> is territorial , with pairs generally bonding for life . Breeding takes place between July and September , with almost no variation across its range . The nest is a bowl @-@ shaped structure of sticks sited high in a tree , or occasionally in a man @-@ made structure such as a <unk> or other building . 
 
 = = Taxonomy and naming = = 
 
 The Australian <unk> was first described by Nicholas <unk> <unk> and Thomas <unk> in 1827 , when they reported George <unk> 's early notes on the species from the Sydney district . Its specific epithet <unk> " <unk> @-@ shaped " is derived from the Greek <unk> / <unk> " <unk> " and <unk> / <unk> " shape " or " form " . The two naturalists regarded the Australian <unk> as very similar in appearance to the <unk> <unk> ( C. <unk> ) of Europe , though they noted it was larger with a longer bill . They did not give it a common name . The location where the type specimen was collected is not recorded , but thought to be in the <unk> district . Christian Ludwig <unk> described <unk> <unk> in 1845 , later determined to be this species . In his 1865 <unk> to the Birds of Australia , John Gould recognised only one species of <unk> in Australia , <unk> <unk> , which he called the white @-@ eyed <unk> . He used Johann Friedrich <unk> 's 1788 name , which <unk> <unk> and <unk> 's description . In 1877 Richard <unk> Sharpe recognised two species , but recorded that the feather bases of the type specimen of C. <unk> were white . He named C. <unk> as the " <unk> " and C. <unk> ( as <unk> <unk> ) the " <unk> " . Scottish naturalist William Robert <unk> @-@ Grant corrected this in 1912 after re @-@ examining the type specimen , clarifying the species as C. <unk> ( <unk> , and incorporating little and forest <unk> ) and C. <unk> ( <unk> <unk> ) . 
 Gregory Mathews described the western subspecies <unk> in 1912 , naming it the southwestern <unk> and noting that it was smaller than the nominate subspecies . He called C. <unk> coronoides the eastern <unk> , listing its range as New South Wales , and described what is now the Australian <unk> as another subspecies , C. <unk> <unk> , calling it the north @-@ western <unk> and recording its range as northwestern Australia . In the same work he listed the <unk> as <unk> <unk> , with a type specimen from <unk> and listing its range as New South Wales . He listed the little <unk> and forest <unk> as subspecies . Mathews had erected C. <unk> in 1911 as the name after declaring <unk> <unk> Gould to be preoccupied ; French @-@ American ornithologist Charles <unk> acted as First <unk> under Article 24 of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature ( <unk> ) Code and discarded C. <unk> as a junior <unk> — in 1788 , <unk> had used the same binomial name to describe the black <unk> — to preserve the stability of the name . This has been followed by later authors . 
 German ornithologist Erwin <unk> <unk> all Australian <unk> plus other species as far as India into a single species , C. <unk> , as he believed there was <unk> between all characteristics such as iris colour , colour of feather bases and plumage . This was <unk> disputed by Mathews . The official <unk> <unk> listed three species ( Australian <unk> , <unk> <unk> and little <unk> ) , with the little <unk> recognised as a fourth species in 1967 and forest <unk> in 1970 . <unk> described C. <unk> in 1943 from a single specimen , now thought to have been an unusual Australian <unk> or an Australian <unk> / <unk> <unk> hybrid . 
 Alternative names sometimes seen include southern <unk> , southern <unk> and Kelly , the last thought to have alluded to the Kelly Gang , though did not appear until the 1920s . Southern <unk> was considered by the <unk> before Australian <unk> was adopted as the official name for the species in 1926 . The term " <unk> " is colloquially applied to any or all species of Australian <unk> . The Australian <unk> was called <unk> by the local <unk> and <unk> inhabitants of the Sydney Basin . 
 
 = = = Evolution and <unk> = = = 
 
 The Australian <unk> 's closest relatives are the other two species of <unk> occurring in Australia : the little <unk> and forest <unk> . The Australian <unk> is also somewhat closely related to the <unk> and little <unk> , although not as closely related as it is to the other <unk> species . Initial single gene genetic analysis of the genus using mitochondrial DNA showed the three <unk> species to belong to one lineage and the two <unk> to another . The genetic separation between species is small and there was a suggestion the little <unk> may be <unk> within the Australian <unk> , though the authors conceded more genetic work was needed . Subsequent <unk> analysis using nuclear DNA by <unk> and colleagues in 2012 showed the eastern and western subspecies of the Australian <unk> to form two clades , almost as genetically distinct as the forest and little <unk> are to each other . This led the authors to propose that the subspecies be recognised as separate species . 
 Ian Rowley proposed that the common ancestor of the five species diverged into a tropical <unk> and temperate <unk> sometime after entering Australia from the north , which molecular evidence indicates occurred in the early <unk> <unk> around 4 million years ago . The <unk> diverged into the ancestor of the forest and little <unk> in the east and Australian <unk> in the west , this split occurring around 2 million years ago in the early Pleistocene . As the climate became cooler and <unk> , the <unk> of central Australia split them entirely . Furthermore , the eastern birds diverged into nomadic little <unk> and , in forested <unk> , forest <unk> . As the climate eventually became warmer , the western birds spread eastwards and almost <unk> forest <unk> on mainland Australia . Rowley noted that the western subspecies of the Australian <unk> had features intermediate between the eastern subspecies of Australian and little <unk> . 
 Two subspecies are recognised : 
 C. c. <unk> , the nominate or eastern subspecies , is found across most of eastern Australia . Its range is also highly correlated with the presence of sheep . This is thought to be because of the frequency of dead animals , which can be an important source of food . <unk> Ian Rowley held that the eastern subspecies was expanding eastwards before European colonisation , and that this suggested it was of younger origin than the western subspecies , which appears static . The advent of agriculture facilitated further spread . 
 C. c. <unk> , the western subspecies , occurs from the head of the Great Australian Bight in South Australia <unk> into Western Australia where its northern limits are Shark Bay and the <unk> @-@ eucalypt boundary line . It is less specialised in its habitat , as it does not share its distribution with the little <unk> , and does not appear to <unk> with the range of sheep . The western subspecies has a slightly lower @-@ pitched call than that of the eastern subspecies , with similarities to calls of the little <unk> . Of smaller size overall , it has a more slender bill and shorter <unk> . There is otherwise no difference in plumage . Intermediate birds are found in the <unk> Peninsula , <unk> Ranges and vicinity of Lake <unk> in South Australia . 
 
 = = Description = = 
 
 Measuring 46 – 53 cm ( 18 – 21 in ) in length with a 100 cm ( 39 in ) wingspan and weighing around 650 g ( 1 @.@ 43 lb ) , the adult Australian <unk> is an all black @-@ bird with a black beak , mouth and tongue and <unk> black or grey @-@ black legs and feet . The tibia is fully feathered and the <unk> is long , and the feet large and strong . It has white irises . The plumage is glossy with a blue @-@ purple to blue @-@ green <unk> , greenish over the ear coverts , depending on light . The underparts are not glossy . The Australian <unk> has throat feathers ( <unk> ) that are <unk> with rounded tips , while the other four species of Australian <unk> have <unk> tips , though this can be difficult to see in the field . The <unk> are also longer than those of the other four species ; when they are raised ( such as when the bird is calling ) , they give the bird an unusual bearded appearance . The upper third of the upper mandible , including the nares and nasal groove , is covered with <unk> , which can be up to 3 cm ( 1 @.@ 2 in ) long . The heavy @-@ set beak is tipped with a slight hook , and is longer than the bird 's head . The wings are long and broad , with the longest of its ten primary feathers ( usually the seventh but occasionally the eighth ) almost reaching the end of the tail when the bird is at rest . The tail is rounded or wedge @-@ shaped . The Australian <unk> can be distinguished from the two species of <unk> occurring in Australia by the grey base of the feathers , which is white in the latter species . The demarcation between pale and black regions on the feather is gradual in the <unk> and sharply delineated in the <unk> . Feather bases are not normally visible when observing birds in the field , but can sometimes be seen on a <unk> day if the feathers are <unk> . Unlike the other four species , the Australian <unk> has a bare patch of skin under , and extending to beside , the bill . This can be hard to <unk> in the field . The three species of <unk> are more heavily set with a broader chest than the two <unk> species , with the forest <unk> the <unk> of all . Relative size of species is only useful when two species can be seen side by side , as the overlap in size is large and the difference in size small . 
 Juveniles resemble adults , but lack throat <unk> , and sometimes have a pink <unk> <unk> . The bill is shorter and shallower ; its base can be pinkish and the tip can be light grey . The plumage is more <unk> and softer in appearance , lacks the glossy highlights and often having a brown tinge . The bare skin on the throat is pink in bird that have recently left the nest . Eye colour varies with age , gradually <unk> from juvenile to adult . <unk> up to four months old have blue @-@ grey irises , juveniles aged from four to fifteen months have dark brown irises , and immature birds have <unk> irises with an inner blue rim around each pupil until age two years and ten months . <unk> birds older than one year develop <unk> , while some pink remains in the <unk> until the bird is two or three years of age . 
 
 = = = <unk> = = = 
 
 The territorial call of the Australian <unk> is a slow , high <unk> @-@ <unk> @-@ <unk> with the last note drawn out . It uses this call to communicate with other Australian <unk> in the area . When giving this call , the species has a horizontal posture , holding its head forward and body parallel to the ground , while perched on a prominent position . It <unk> its <unk> and lowers its tail , and sometimes holds its beak open between calls . In contrast , the little <unk> and forest <unk> hold their bodies in an upright posture . This call becomes louder if <unk> <unk> upon the Australian <unk> 's territory . The five Australian species are very difficult to tell apart , with the call being the <unk> way to do so , although the drawing @-@ out of the final note — long held to be solely recorded for the Australian <unk> — has been recorded for the other species and is hence not diagnostic . 
 The volume , pitch , tempo and order of notes can be changed depending on the message the Australian <unk> intends to convey . There are a variety of contact calls : a pair often makes a low <unk> sound when <unk> each other while roosting , and members of a flock carry on with a quiet chattering while at rest . Birds make a call and answer sequence if temporarily out of sight of one another while foraging . Birds in flocks make a single high @-@ pitched <unk> while flying over another territory as a transit call to signify they are just passing through . An Australian <unk> will give a longer <unk> with a downward <unk> to signify its return to the nest to its mate . 
 
 = = Distribution and habitat = = 
 
 The Australian <unk> is common throughout eastern Australia , and southern Western Australia ( the populations being connected by a narrow strip across the <unk> Plain ) , but it is rarer and more scattered in the north , with isolated sightings in Cape York at <unk> , <unk> Creek and the Mitchell River , and becoming more common south of <unk> in central Queensland . It is found throughout New South Wales , though is uncommon in the northeast of the state . It is rare in the Australian <unk> , being replaced there by the little <unk> . It occurs across Victoria and eastern South Australia , through the <unk> Peninsula and <unk> Plain into Western Australia , across the state north to the <unk> River . It is found on some offshore islands such as <unk> Island and <unk> Island . It is a rare <unk> to Lord Howe Island . 
 The Australian <unk> can be found in a wide range of natural and modified habitats . It requires available water and trees ( or buildings ) to roost in or perch on . <unk> habitats include eucalypt @-@ dominated <unk> forest , and farmland adjacent to trees . It is also found in heath and <unk> . In areas where it occurs with the little <unk> , namely over much of central New South Wales , Victoria and into South Australia , the Australian <unk> is restricted to more forested areas while the latter species prefers more open areas . Similarly , in inland Australia it can share range with the little <unk> , as the two do not appear to compete . However , the ranges of similar @-@ sized forest <unk> and <unk> <unk> only narrowly overlap with the Australian <unk> as all three compete with each other . In central and western regions , Australian <unk> and <unk> <unk> <unk> for the scattered uncommon trees and <unk> , and only one or the other are found there . It co @-@ occurs with the forest <unk> in northeastern New South Wales from Port Stephens northwards . The Australian <unk> has adapted very well to human habitation in some cities and is the most common <unk> in Canberra , Sydney and Perth ; in Melbourne and Adelaide it is replaced by the little <unk> , and by the <unk> <unk> in Brisbane . Its large range , abundance and increasing population mean it is classified as Least Concern on the IUCN Red List . 
 
 = = Behaviour = = 
 
 <unk> in distinguishing Australian <unk> has hampered understanding of seasonal movements . The Australian <unk> is thought to be largely sedentary , with most movement of over 16 km ( 9 @.@ 9 mi ) due to flocks of non @-@ breeding <unk> birds . <unk> birds leave their parents and join flocks when they are four or five months old . Smaller flocks of 8 – 30 birds stay within an area of around 260 square kilometres , while larger flocks of up to 300 birds may travel hundreds of kilometres seeking food . 
 A single breeding pair and their brood can occupy a territory of up to around 120 hectares ( 300 acres ) and remains there year @-@ round , though groups of <unk> may enter this area to forage . Australian <unk> will defend their territory by chasing , dive @-@ bombing and occasionally striking the backs of birds of prey , foxes or even people . They generally mate for life , though occasionally one male has been found to be mated with two females in adjacent territories . If the female dies , the male Australian <unk> maintains the territory and finds another mate , while if the male bird is lost , the female abandons the territory . No courtship behaviour has been observed , and species that mate for life often lack elaborate courting displays . Once they begin breeding at three years of age , they live another four to five years on average . During this time they produce two surviving young each year on average . The longest @-@ lived Australian <unk> recorded is an adult ( of at least 3 years of age ) that was banded and recaptured alive 12 years and 5 months later . 
 Australian <unk> generally walk when moving around on the ground , though do hop when <unk> . They <unk> themselves frequently , particularly when roosting in the middle of the day . They also engage in <unk> , where birds will <unk> each other 's head and neck . This takes place particularly in autumn , winter and spring , and is important in pair bonding . Either member may initiate it , generally by landing near the other bird , <unk> next to its mate , then <unk> its head forward and presenting its nape . 
 
 = = = Feeding = = = 
 
 The Australian <unk> is omnivorous , though eats more meat than smaller <unk> . Its diet in summer contains a high proportion of insects , while more plant items are eaten in autumn . <unk> makes up over half its diet in winter . <unk> commonly eaten include spiders , <unk> , <unk> ( which <unk> behead before eating ) , grasshoppers , <unk> and <unk> ( especially of the family <unk> ) , which are important in feeding nestlings . Australian <unk> sometimes eat <unk> ( <unk> <unk> ) from the edges of dams . Unusually for a ground @-@ feeding <unk> , earthworms are rarely eaten . Australian <unk> have been reported killing birds of such size as young <unk> ( <unk> <unk> ) and starlings ( Sturnus vulgaris ) . Most mammals are eaten as <unk> , as many species are too large for the <unk> to kill , though young rabbits are a frequent prey item . Australian <unk> drink water frequently , up to ten times a day in hot weather . Birds have been observed <unk> pieces of meat in water before eating them , as well as doing the same with hard <unk> to make them <unk> and soft . 
 Australian <unk> are intelligent birds , and like many other <unk> have innovative methods of seeking out food . <unk> takes place in the early morning or late afternoon ; birds rest in the <unk> part of the day . Food is taken mainly from the ground , birds either finding objects while flying overhead , or by walking along and looking . However , they occasionally feed in trees — Australian <unk> forage eucalypt foliage for Christmas beetles ( <unk> ) , and devote a substantial amount of time to look for nests and eggs to eat . They have also been known to take golf balls from <unk> , possibly <unk> them for eggs . <unk> use their bill rather than their feet to explore or turn items on the ground ( rocks or sticks ) over , or hold or <unk> food while flying . They have also been recorded using fence posts as <unk> to <unk> snails against before eating them . Australian <unk> most often eat food where they find it unless taking food back for nestlings . Occasionally they have been observed <unk> <unk> or a killed animal in a hole nearby to store it . They can pack <unk> meat in their mouth under their tongue . Australian <unk> have adapted well to eating food scraps in urban areas , such as school playgrounds , rubbish tips , <unk> outside <unk> or restaurants , <unk> , <unk> and <unk> . In one isolated study , they were observed feeding on nectar from eucalypt flowers . Australian <unk> sometimes forage in mixed @-@ species flocks with any of the other four species of Australian <unk> . Sometimes they are aggressive with little <unk> if both are at a food source and drive them off , though not if the smaller species greatly <unk> the larger . 
 
 = = = Breeding = = = 
 
 Australian <unk> begin breeding once they are three years old . Breeding season is from July to September , with no substantial difference in timing across its range around the country despite it inhabiting a range of diverse climates and habitats across 19 degrees of latitude . Rowley has pointed out this is unusual for a bird species with a wide range and has postulated that breeding is initiated by day length . Rarely , breeding can take place in May , June or October . Australian <unk> generally nest in tall trees , never near to the ground as some species do . The nest also functions as a lookout post and so tall or <unk> trees are selected . The <unk> occasionally nest on buildings , telegraph poles , or tall <unk> which allow the species to occupy areas lacking in tall trees . <unk> may have assisted the spread of the species in North Queensland and the Northern Territory . The highest recorded <unk> nest in Australia was found atop the <unk> Tower in Sydney . 
 Nests are generally large and untidy , consisting of a bowl or platform of sticks lined with grasses , <unk> , and feathers that can be up to 5 cm ( 2 @.@ 0 in ) thick . As they are relatively heavy , they are built on larger forks in trees rather than out in the canopy . Building the nest is often time @-@ consuming initially as the birds try ( and often fail ) to wedge sticks , which are 30 – 60 cm ( 12 – 24 in ) long and 0 @.@ 6 – 1 @.@ 2 cm ( 1 ⁄ 4 – 1 ⁄ 2 in ) thick , into the tree fork to make a platform . <unk> sticks and rootlets are used to make the bowl before the bowl is lined with feathers . Both birds build the nest , with the female taking over the lining of the nest while the male brings her material . New nests are built each year generally , as the re @-@ use of old ones might spread disease or parasites — nests become <unk> with <unk> as the nestlings grow and the parents cannot keep up with its removal . Furthermore , old nests often <unk> within twelve months due to their exposed locations . The female develops a brood patch — a patch of bare skin on the bird 's underparts that <unk> and becomes much more extensive from around three weeks before the first egg is laid . The skin itself is <unk> and wrinkled , and does not get re @-@ feathered until December after the breeding season has finished . 
 Their <unk> locations makes monitoring of Australian <unk> nests difficult . A clutch can comprise up to six eggs , though usually four or five are laid , with five being the <unk> number . Measuring 45 by 30 mm ( 1 3 ⁄ 4 by 1 1 ⁄ 4 in ) , eggs are pale green or bluish @-@ green and <unk> with darker olive , brown and blackish markings . <unk> are quite variable , and thus which Australian <unk> laid them cannot be reliably identified . Incubation of the eggs is done solely by the female over roughly 20 days . Incubation is intermittent initially , becoming constant by the time the third or fourth egg is laid . Only one brood is raised per year , though a second clutch may be laid if the first clutch is lost early in the season . Late clutches have poor survival rates , possibly due to chicks getting <unk> on hot days as the year progresses or being eaten by wedge @-@ tailed eagles . The chicks are <unk> and <unk> ; that is , they are born helpless , naked and blind , and remain in the nest for an extended period . They have pink skin until 5 days of age , when feathers under the skin turn it grey . They lose their egg tooth at the same time . Their eyes begin opening at 5 to 6 days of age and are fully open by 11 to 12 days , by which time their feathers begin emerging . At 14 days , their primary feathers begin emerging , and they are fully feathered by 35 – 36 days old . They leave the nest at 40 – 45 days of age , and stay with the parents for three to four months after that . They follow their parents and beg for food for the first month outside the nest but are feeding themselves by the third month . Young birds are often attacked when they enter neighbouring territories , and <unk> ensue as their parents try to defend them and herd them back . 
 
