 Lady Mary <unk> Montagu ( 1689 – <unk> ) was an <unk> , a writer and the wife of a Member of Parliament . In <unk> , her husband , Edward <unk> Montagu , was appointed British Ambassador in Istanbul . She followed him there and two weeks after her arrival discovered the local practice of protection against smallpox by <unk> – the injection of <unk> from smallpox victims into the skin . Her younger brother had died of smallpox , and she too had had the disease . <unk> to spare her five @-@ year @-@ old son Edward from similar suffering , she ordered the embassy surgeon Charles <unk> to <unk> him . On her return to London , she asked <unk> to <unk> her four @-@ year @-@ old daughter in the presence of the king 's <unk> . Later , Montagu persuaded the Prince and Princess of Wales to sponsor a public demonstration of the procedure . Six prisoners who had been condemned to death and were awaiting execution at Newgate Prison were offered a full pardon for serving as the subjects of the public experiment . They accepted and were <unk> in 1721 . All the prisoners recovered from the procedure . To test its protective effect one of them , a nineteen @-@ year @-@ old woman , was ordered to sleep in the same bed as a ten @-@ year @-@ old smallpox victim for six weeks . She did not contract the disease . 
