 = = 20th and 21st centuries = = 
 
 At the turn of the 20th century , evidence for the existence of viruses was obtained from experiments with <unk> that had pores too small for bacteria to pass through ; the term " <unk> virus " was coined to describe them . Until the 1930s most scientists believed that viruses were small bacteria , but following the invention of the electron microscope in 1931 they were shown to be completely different , to a degree that not all scientists were convinced they were anything other than <unk> of toxic proteins . The situation changed radically when it was discovered that viruses contain genetic material in the form of DNA or RNA . Once they were recognised as distinct biological entities they were soon shown to be the cause of numerous infections of plants , animals and even bacteria . 
 Of the many diseases of humans that were found to be caused by viruses in the 20th century one , smallpox , has been eradicated . The diseases caused by viruses such as HIV and influenza virus have proved to be more difficult to control . Other diseases , such as those caused by <unk> , are presenting new challenges . 
 As humans have changed their behaviour during history , so have viruses . In ancient times the human population was too small for <unk> to occur and , in the case of some viruses , too small for them to survive . In the 20th and 21st century increasing population densities , revolutionary changes in agriculture and farming methods , and high speed travel have contributed to the spread of new viruses and the re @-@ appearance of old ones . Like smallpox , some viral diseases might be conquered , but new ones , such as severe acute respiratory syndrome ( <unk> ) , will continue to emerge . Although <unk> are still the most powerful weapon against viruses , in recent decades <unk> drugs have been developed to specifically target viruses as they replicate in their hosts . The 2009 influenza pandemic showed how rapidly new strains of viruses continue to spread around the world , despite efforts to contain them . 
 <unk> in virus discovery and control continue to be made . Human <unk> , which is a cause of respiratory infections including pneumonia , was discovered in 2001 . A vaccine for the <unk> that cause cervical cancer was developed between 2002 and 2006 . In 2005 , human T <unk> viruses 3 and 4 were discovered . In 2008 the WHO Global <unk> <unk> Initiative was re @-@ launched with a plan to eradicate <unk> by 2015 . In 2010 , the largest virus , <unk> <unk> was discovered to infect <unk> . These giant viruses have renewed interest in the role viruses play in evolution and their position in the tree of life . 
 
 = = = <unk> eradication = = = 
 
 <unk> virus was a major cause of death in the 20th century , killing about 300 million people . It has probably killed more humans than any other virus . In 1966 an agreement was reached by the World Health Assembly ( the decision @-@ making body of the World Health Organisation ) to start an " intensified smallpox eradication programme " and attempt to eradicate the disease within ten years . At the time , smallpox was still endemic in 31 countries including Brazil , the whole of the Indian sub @-@ continent , Indonesia and sub @-@ Saharan Africa . This ambitious goal was considered <unk> for several reasons : the vaccine afforded exceptional protection ; there was only one type of the virus ; there were no animals that naturally carried it ; the incubation period of the infection was known and rarely varied from 12 days ; and infections always gave rise to symptoms , so it was clear who had the disease . 
 Following mass <unk> , disease detection and containment were central to the eradication campaign . As soon as cases were detected , the victims were isolated as were their close contacts , who were <unk> . <unk> came quickly ; by 1970 smallpox was no longer endemic in western Africa , nor , by 1971 , in Brazil . By 1973 , smallpox remained endemic only in the Indian sub @-@ continent , <unk> and Ethiopia . Finally , after 13 years of coordinated disease surveillance and <unk> campaigns throughout the world , the World Health Organisation declared smallpox eradicated in 1979 . Although the main weapon used was <unk> virus , which was used as the vaccine , no one seems to know exactly where <unk> virus came from ; it is not the strain of <unk> that Edward <unk> used , and it is not a weakened form of smallpox . 
 The eradication campaign led to the death of Janet Parker ( c . 1938 – 1978 ) and the subsequent suicide of the smallpox expert Henry <unk> ( 1930 – 1978 ) . Parker was an employee of the University of Birmingham who worked in the same building as <unk> 's smallpox laboratory . She was infected by a strain of smallpox virus that <unk> 's team had been investigating . <unk> of the accident and having blamed himself for it , <unk> committed suicide . 
 Before the September 11 attacks on the United States in 2001 , the World Health Organisation proposed the destruction of all the known remaining stocks of smallpox virus that were kept in laboratories in the US and Russia . <unk> of <unk> using smallpox virus and the possible need for the virus in the development of drugs to treat the infection have put an end to this plan . Had the destruction gone ahead , smallpox virus might have been the first to be made extinct by human intervention . 
 
 = = = <unk> = = = 
 
 Before the introduction of <unk> in the US in the 1960s there were more than 500 @,@ 000 cases each year resulting in about 400 deaths . In developed countries children were mainly infected between the ages of three and five years old , but in developing countries half the children were infected before the age of two . In the US and the UK , there were regular annual or <unk> <unk> of the disease , which depended on the number of children born each year . The current epidemic strain evolved in the first part of the 20th century – probably between 1908 and 1943 . 
 In London between 1950 and 1968 there were <unk> every two years , but in Liverpool , which had a higher birth rate , there was an annual cycle of <unk> . During the Great Depression in the US before the Second World War the birth rate was low , and <unk> of <unk> were sporadic . After the war the birth rate increased , and <unk> occurred regularly every two years . In developing countries with very high birth rates , <unk> occurred every year . <unk> is still a major problem in densely populated , less @-@ developed countries with high birth rates and lacking effective <unk> campaigns . 
 By the mid @-@ 1970s , following a mass <unk> programme that was known as " make <unk> a memory " , the incidence of <unk> in the US had fallen by 90 per cent . Similar <unk> campaigns in other countries have reduced the levels of infection by 99 per cent over the past 50 years . <unk> individuals remain a source of infection and include those who have migrated from countries with ineffective <unk> schedules , or who refuse the vaccine or choose not to have their children <unk> . <unk> are the only natural host of <unk> virus . <unk> to the disease following an infection is lifelong ; that afforded by <unk> is long term but eventually <unk> . 
 The use of the vaccine has been controversial . In 1998 , Andrew Wakefield and his colleagues published a <unk> research paper and he claimed to link the MMR vaccine with autism . The study was widely reported and fed concern about the safety of <unk> . Wakefield 's research was identified as <unk> and in 2010 , he was struck off the UK medical register and can no longer <unk> medicine in the UK . In the wake of the controversy , the MMR <unk> rate in the UK fell from 92 per cent in 1995 , to less than 80 per cent in 2003 . Cases of <unk> rose from 56 in 1998 to <unk> in 2008 , and similar increases occurred throughout Europe . In April 2013 , an epidemic of <unk> in Wales in the UK broke out , which mainly affected teenagers who had not been <unk> . Despite this controversy , <unk> has been eliminated from Finland , Sweden and Cuba . Japan abolished mandatory <unk> in 1992 , and in 1995 – 1997 more than 200 @,@ 000 cases were reported in the country . <unk> remains a public health problem in Japan , where it is now endemic ; a National <unk> <unk> Plan was established in December 2007 , with a view to eliminating the disease from the country . The possibility of global elimination of <unk> has been debated in medical literature since the introduction of the vaccine in the 1960s . Should the current campaign to eradicate <unk> be successful , it is likely that the debate will be renewed . 
 
 = = = <unk> = = = 
 
 During the summers of the mid @-@ 20th century , parents in the US and Europe <unk> the annual appearance of <unk> ( or <unk> ) , which was commonly known as " <unk> <unk> " . The disease was rare at the beginning of the century , and worldwide there were only a few thousand cases per year , but by the 1950s there were 60 @,@ 000 cases each year in the US alone and an average of 2 @,@ 300 in England and Wales . 
 During 1916 and 1917 there had been a major epidemic in the US ; 27 @,@ 000 cases and 6 @,@ 000 deaths were recorded , with 9 @,@ 000 cases in New York City . At the time nobody knew how the virus was spreading . Many of the city 's inhabitants , including scientists , thought that impoverished <unk> @-@ dwelling immigrants were to blame even though the prevalence of the disease was higher in the more prosperous districts such as <unk> Island – a pattern that had also been seen in cities like Philadelphia . Many other <unk> countries were affected at the same time . In particular , before the outbreaks in the US , large <unk> had occurred in Sweden . 
 The reason for the rise of <unk> in <unk> countries in the 20th century has never been fully explained . The disease is caused by a virus that is passed from person to person by the <unk> @-@ oral route , and naturally <unk> only humans . It is a paradox that it became a problem during times of improved sanitation and increasing <unk> . Although the virus was discovered at the beginning of the 20th century , its <unk> was <unk> until the 1950s . It is now known that fewer than two per cent of individuals who are infected develop the disease , and most infections are mild . During <unk> the virus was effectively everywhere , which explains why public health officials were unable to isolate a source . 
 Following the development of <unk> in the mid @-@ 1950s , mass <unk> campaigns took place in many countries . In the US , after a campaign promoted by the March of <unk> , the annual number of <unk> cases fell dramatically ; the last outbreak was in 1979 . In 1988 the World Health Organisation along with others launched the Global <unk> <unk> Initiative , and by 1994 the Americas were declared to be free of disease , followed by the Pacific region in 2000 and Europe in 2003 . At the end of 2012 , only 223 cases were reported by the World Health Organisation . <unk> <unk> type 1 infections , 122 occurred in Nigeria , one in Chad , 58 in Pakistan and 37 in Afghanistan . <unk> teams often face danger ; seven <unk> were murdered in Pakistan and nine in Nigeria at the beginning of 2013 . In Pakistan , the campaign was further hampered by the murder on 26 February 2013 of a police officer who was providing security . 
 
 = = = AIDS = = = 
 
 The human <unk> virus ( HIV ) is the virus that – when the infection is not treated – can cause AIDS ( acquired <unk> syndrome ) . Most <unk> believe that HIV originated in sub @-@ Saharan Africa during the 20th century , and over 70 million individuals have been infected by the virus . By 2011 , an estimated 35 million had died from AIDS , making it one of the most destructive <unk> in recorded history . HIV @-@ 1 is one of the most significant viruses to have emerged in the last quarter of the 20th century . When , in 1981 , a scientific article was published that reported the deaths of five young gay men , no one knew that they had died from AIDS . The full scale of the epidemic – and that the virus had been silently emerging over several decades – was not known . 
 HIV crossed the species barrier between <unk> and humans in Africa in the early decades of the 20th century . During the years that followed there were enormous social changes and turmoil in Africa . Population shifts were unprecedented as vast numbers of people moved from rural farms to the expanding cities , and the virus was spread from remote regions to densely populated urban <unk> . The incubation period for AIDS is around 10 years , so a global epidemic starting in the early 1980s is credible . At this time there was much <unk> and <unk> . The " out of Africa " theory for the origin of the HIV pandemic was not well received by Africans , who felt that the " blame " was <unk> . This led the World Health Assembly to pass a 1987 resolution , which stated that HIV is " a naturally occurring [ virus ] of undetermined geographic origin " . 
 The HIV pandemic has challenged communities and brought about social changes throughout the world . Opinions on sexuality are more openly discussed . <unk> on sexual practices and drug use – which were once taboo – is sponsored by many governments and their healthcare providers . <unk> on the ethics of provision and cost of anti @-@ <unk> drugs , particularly in poorer countries , have highlighted <unk> in healthcare and stimulated far @-@ reaching legislative changes . In developing countries the impact of HIV / AIDS has been profound ; key organisations such as healthcare , defense and civil services have been severely disrupted . Life expectancy has fallen . In Zimbabwe , for example , life expectancy was 79 years in 1991 but by 2001 it had fallen to 39 years . 
 
 = = = <unk> = = = 
 
 When influenza virus undergoes a genetic shift many humans have no immunity to the new strain , and if the population of susceptible individuals is high enough to maintain the chain of infection , <unk> occur . The genetic changes usually happen when different strains of the virus co @-@ infect animals , particularly birds and <unk> . Although many viruses of vertebrates are restricted to one species , influenza virus is an exception . The last pandemic of the 19th century occurred in 1899 and resulted in the deaths of 250 @,@ 000 people in Europe . The virus , which originated in Russia or Asia , was the first to be rapidly spread by people on trains and <unk> . 
 A new strain of the virus emerged in 1918 , and the subsequent pandemic of Spanish flu was one of the worst natural disasters in history . The death toll was enormous ; throughout the world around 50 million people died from the infection . There were 550 @,@ 000 reported deaths caused by the disease in the US , ten times the country 's losses during the First World War , and 228 @,@ 000 deaths in the UK . In India there were more than 20 million deaths , and in Western Samoa 22 per cent of the population died . Although cases of influenza occurred every winter , there were only two other <unk> in the 20th century . 
 In 1957 another new strain of the virus emerged and caused a pandemic of Asian flu ; although the virus was not as <unk> as the 1918 strain , over one million died worldwide . The next pandemic occurred when Hong Kong flu emerged in 1968 , a new strain of the virus that replaced the 1957 strain . <unk> mainly the elderly , the 1968 pandemic was the least severe , but 33 @,@ 800 were killed in the US . New strains of influenza virus often originate in East Asia ; in rural China the concentration of ducks , pigs , and humans in close proximity is the highest in the world . 
 The most recent pandemic occurred in 2009 , but none of the last three has caused anything near the devastation seen in 1918 . <unk> why the strain of influenza that emerged in 1918 was so devastating is a question that still remains <unk> . 
 
 = = = Yellow fever , <unk> and other <unk> = = = 
 
 <unk> are viruses that are transmitted to humans and other vertebrates by blood @-@ sucking insects . These viruses are diverse ; the term " <unk> " – which was derived from " <unk> @-@ borne virus " – is no longer used in formal taxonomy because many species of virus are known to be spread in this way . There are more than 500 species of <unk> , but in the 1930s only three were known to cause disease in humans : yellow fever virus , <unk> virus and <unk> fever virus . More than 100 of such viruses are now known to cause human diseases including <unk> . 
 Yellow fever is the most notorious disease caused by a <unk> . The last major epidemic in the US occurred in 1905 . During the building of the Panama Canal thousands of workers died from the disease . Yellow fever originated in Africa and the virus was brought to the Americas on cargo ships , which were <unk> the <unk> <unk> <unk> that carries the virus . The first recorded epidemic in Africa occurred in Ghana , in West Africa , in 1926 . In the 1930s the disease re @-@ emerged in Brazil . Fred <unk> , an American <unk> ( 1893 – 1977 ) , discovered the importance of the sylvatic cycle of infection in non @-@ human hosts , and that infection of humans was a " dead end " that broke this cycle . Although the yellow fever vaccine is one of the most successful ever developed , <unk> continue to occur . In 1986 – 91 in West Africa , over 20 @,@ 000 people were infected , 4 @,@ 000 of whom died . 
 In the 1930s , St. Louis <unk> , eastern <unk> <unk> and western <unk> <unk> emerged in the US . The virus that causes La <unk> <unk> was discovered in the 1960s , and West Nile virus arrived in New York in 1999 . As of 2010 , <unk> virus is the most prevalent <unk> and increasingly <unk> strains of the virus have spread across Asia and the Americas . 
 
 = = = <unk> viruses = = = 
 
 <unk> is a disease of the liver that has been recognised since antiquity . Symptoms include <unk> , a <unk> of the skin , eyes and body fluids . There are numerous causes , including viruses – particularly <unk> A virus , <unk> B virus and <unk> C virus . Throughout history <unk> of <unk> have been reported , mainly affecting soldiers at war . This " campaign <unk> " was common in the Middle Ages . It occurred among Napoleon 's armies and during most of the major conflicts of the 19th and 20th centuries , including the American Civil War , where over 40 @,@ 000 cases and around 150 deaths were reported . The viruses that cause epidemic <unk> were not discovered until the middle of the 20th century . The names for epidemic <unk> , <unk> A , and for blood @-@ borne infectious <unk> , <unk> B , were first used in 1947 , following a publication in 1946 giving evidence that the two diseases were distinct . In the 1960s , the first virus that could cause <unk> was discovered . This was <unk> B virus , which was named after the disease it causes . <unk> A virus was discovered in 1974 . The discovery of <unk> B virus and the invention of tests to detect it have radically changed many medical , and some cosmetic procedures . The screening of donated blood , which was introduced in the early 1970s , has dramatically reduced the transmission of the virus . <unk> of human blood plasma and Factor VIII collected before 1975 often contained infectious levels of <unk> B virus . Until the late 1960s , <unk> needles were often reused by medical professionals , and tattoo artists ' needles were a common source of infection . In the late 1990s , needle exchange programmes were established in Europe and the US to prevent the spread of infections by intravenous drug users . These measures also helped to reduce the subsequent impact of HIV and <unk> C virus . 
 
 = = = Non @-@ human animal viruses = = = 
 
 <unk> are outbreaks ( <unk> ) of disease among non @-@ human animals . During the 20th century significant <unk> of viral diseases in animals , particularly livestock , occurred worldwide . The many diseases caused by viruses included foot @-@ and @-@ mouth disease , <unk> of cattle , avian and <unk> influenza , <unk> fever and <unk> of sheep . <unk> diseases of livestock can be devastating both to farmers and the wider community , as the outbreak of foot @-@ and @-@ mouth disease in the UK in 2001 showed . 
 First appearing in East Africa in 1891 , <unk> , a disease of cattle , spread rapidly across Africa . By 1892 , 95 per cent of the cattle in East Africa had died . This resulted in a famine that devastated the farmers and nomadic people , some of whom were entirely dependent on their cattle . Two thirds of the population of Maasai people died . The situation was made worse by <unk> of smallpox that followed in the wake of the famine . In the early years of the 20th century <unk> was common in Asia and parts of Europe . The prevalence of the disease was steadily reduced during the century by control measures that included <unk> . By 1908 Europe was free from the disease . <unk> did occur following the Second World War , but these were quickly controlled . The prevalence of the disease increased in Asia , and in 1957 Thailand had to appeal for aid because so many <unk> had died that the <unk> fields could not be prepared for rice growing . Russia west of the <unk> Mountains remained free from the disease – Lenin approved several laws on the control of the disease – but cattle in eastern Russia were constantly infected with <unk> that originated in Mongolia and China where the prevalence remained high . India controlled the spread of the disease , which had retained a foothold in the southern states of Tamil Nadu and <unk> , throughout the 20th century , and had eradicated the disease by 1995 . Africa suffered two major <unk> in the 1920s and 1980s . There was a severe outbreak in Somalia in 1928 and the disease was widespread in the country until 1953 . In the 1980s , outbreaks in Tanzania and Kenya were controlled by the use of 26 million doses of vaccine , and a recurrence of the disease in 1997 was suppressed by an intensive <unk> campaign . By the end of the century <unk> had been eradicated from most countries . A few pockets of infection remained in Ethiopia and Sudan , and in 1994 the Global <unk> <unk> Programme was launched by the Food and Agriculture Organi