 = <unk> 6 = 
 
 <unk> 6 ( Russian : <unk> @-@ 6 ; lit . <unk> 6 ) , <unk> @-@ 5 , was a Soviet orbital space station , the eighth flown as part of the <unk> programme . <unk> on 29 September 1977 by a <unk> rocket , the station was the first of the ' second @-@ generation ' type of space station . <unk> 6 possessed several revolutionary advances over the earlier Soviet space stations , which it nevertheless resembled in overall design . These included the addition of a second <unk> port , a new main propulsion system and the station 's primary scientific instrument , the <unk> @-@ <unk> <unk> telescope . The addition of the second <unk> port made crew <unk> and station resupply by <unk> Progress <unk> possible for the first time . The early <unk> stations had no means of resupply or removing accumulated garbage ( aside from the limited amount that <unk> could carry in their Soyuz spacecraft ) , nor could the propulsion system be <unk> once it exhausted its propellant supply . Consequently , once the <unk> launched with the station were used up , its mission had to be concluded and as a result , manned missions had a maximum duration of three months . Progress spacecraft could now bring fresh supplies and propellant and also be used to dispose of waste , which was then destroyed once the spacecraft was <unk> . 
 Five crew <unk> took place over the station 's lifespan , in late 1977 @-@ early 1978 , late 1978 , mid @-@ 1979 , mid @-@ 1980 , and early 1981 , including <unk> from Warsaw Pact countries as part of the <unk> programme . These crews were responsible for carrying out the primary missions of <unk> 6 , including astronomy , Earth @-@ resources observations and the study of the effect of <unk> on the human body . Following the completion of these missions and the launch of its successor , <unk> 7 , <unk> 6 was <unk> on 29 July 1982 , almost five years after its launch . 
 
 = = Description = = 
 
 <unk> 6 , launched on a <unk> <unk> rocket on 29 September 1977 , marked the switch from engineering development stations to routine operations , and united the most effective elements from each of the previous stations . Its navigation system , made up of the Delta semi @-@ automatic computer to depict the station 's orbit and the <unk> system to control its orientation , was based on that used on <unk> 4 , as was its power system , which consisted of a trio of <unk> solar panels together producing a peak of 4 <unk> of power over 51 m ² . The station 's thermal regulation systems , which made use of a sophisticated arrangement of <unk> and <unk> , was also derived from that used on <unk> 4 . In addition , <unk> 6 made use of environmental systems first used on <unk> 3 , and controlled its orientation using <unk> first tested on that station . 
 The most important feature on <unk> 6 , however , was the addition of a second <unk> port on the aft end of the station , which allowed two spacecraft to be docked at once . This , in turn , allowed resident crews to receive shorter , ' visiting ' expeditions whilst they remained on board , and for crew <unk> to take place . In addition , it allowed Soyuz spacecraft that had exceeded their operating lifespan to be returned to Earth and replaced by fresh ones ( the Soyuz <unk> used from 1972 @-@ 81 had a maximum operating lifespan of three months ) . Such <unk> , with one expedition <unk> the station only after the next had arrived , permitted the long sought @-@ after aim of continuous occupation to move a step closer . The very first long @-@ duration crew to visit the station broke a long @-@ standing endurance record set on board the American <unk> station , staying 96 days in orbit , whilst the longest expedition lasted 185 days . Some of the visiting expeditions were flown as part of the <unk> programme , with non @-@ Soviet <unk> visiting the station . <unk> <unk> of <unk> , the first space traveller not from the US or USSR , visited <unk> 6 in 1978 , and the station hosted <unk> from Hungary , Poland , Romania , Cuba , Mongolia , Vietnam , and East Germany . 
 The <unk> of the two ports was fitted with <unk> to allow the station to be <unk> by <unk> Progress spacecraft . These <unk> , which brought supplies and extra equipment to keep the station <unk> , helped ensure that the crew were always able to carry out useful scientific work aboard the station . In all , twelve Progress flights delivered over 20 tonnes of equipment , supplies and fuel . 
 The addition of the extra <unk> port caused the adoption of the <unk> @-@ derived twin @-@ chamber propulsion system first used on <unk> 3 and 5 , with the two engine <unk> — each producing 2 @.@ 9 <unk> of thrust — mounted <unk> on either side of the aft port . <unk> 6 introduced a Unified <unk> System , with both the engines and the station 's control <unk> running on <unk> <unk> and nitrogen tetroxide , drawn from a common set of pressurized tanks , allowing the <unk> capabilities of the visiting Progress tankers to be exploited to the maximum effect . The entire engine and fuel storage assembly was contained within an <unk> bay at the rear of the station , which was the same diameter as the main pressurized compartment . However , the replacement of the Soyuz engine used on previous stations with the bay meant that the station kept a similar overall length to its predecessors . The main engines could not be fired if the rear <unk> port was in use , hence any orbital maneuvers during this time had to be performed by the visiting spacecraft . 
 <unk> 6 's propulsion system experienced a serious <unk> during the second crew <unk> in 1978 and was not usable again for the remainder of the station 's lifespan . As a consequence , it was limited to firing its attitude control <unk> and visiting spacecraft had to perform orbital adjustments . After each crew <unk> ended , it was necessary for Progress and <unk> spacecraft to boost the station into a high orbit so it wouldn 't decay until the next <unk> began . 
 To enable <unk> , <unk> 6 was equipped with an inward @-@ opening <unk> hatch on the side of the forward transfer compartment , which could be used as an <unk> in a similar way to the system used on <unk> 4 . This compartment contained two new semi @-@ rigid <unk> which allowed much greater flexibility than earlier suits , and could be <unk> within five minutes in case of an emergency . Finally , the station offered considerable improvements in living conditions over previous outposts , with machinery being <unk> , the crews being provided with designated ' <unk> ' for sleeping and the <unk> of the station with a shower and extensive <unk> . 
 
 = = = <unk> = = = 
 
 The primary instrument carried aboard the station was the <unk> @-@ <unk> <unk> telescope , which could carry out astronomical observations in the infrared , ultraviolet and <unk> spectra using a 1 @.@ 5 metre @-@ diameter mirror which was operated in <unk> conditions at around − 269 ° C. The telescope could be operated only when <unk> 6 was on the night side of the Earth , and had its cover closed for the rest of the time . 
 The second major instrument was the <unk> @-@ <unk> <unk> camera , which carried out Earth @-@ resources observations . An improved form of a camera first tested on Soyuz 22 , the camera captured an area of 165 × 220 kilometres with each image , down to a resolution of 20 metres . Each image was captured simultaneously in six bands in 1200 @-@ frame <unk> , which required regular replacement due to the <unk> effects of radiation . <unk> 6 also featured a <unk> @-@ 140 stereoscopic topographic mapping camera with a focal length of 140 <unk> , which captured images of 450 × 450 kilometres with a resolution of 50 metres in the visible and infrared spectra , which could be operated either <unk> or by the resident crews . The photographic capabilities of the station were , therefore , extensive , and the Soviet Ministry of Agriculture had planted a number of specifically selected crops at test sites to examine the capabilities of the cameras . 
 To further expand its scientific capabilities , <unk> 6 was equipped with 20 <unk> for observations , two scientific <unk> to expose equipment to space or <unk> rubbish , and various pieces of apparatus to carry out biological experiments . Later on during the flight , a Progress spacecraft delivered an external telescope , the <unk> @-@ 10 radio observatory , which incorporated a directional antenna and five <unk> . The antenna was deployed on the rear <unk> assembly , with the controller remaining inside the station , and was used for both astronomical and meteorological observations . 
 
 = = Support craft = = 
 
 <unk> 6 was primarily supported by the manned Soyuz spacecraft , which carried out crew <unk> and would also have been used in the event of an emergency evacuation . The ferries docked automatically to the station , making use of the new <unk> automatic <unk> system , and were used by departing crews to return to Earth at the end of their flight . 
 The station was the first to be able to be <unk> by the newly developed <unk> Progress <unk> , although they could only dock at the rear port , as the front port lacked the <unk> used to refuel the propulsion system . The <unk> docked automatically to the station via the <unk> , and were then opened and emptied by the <unk> on board , whilst transfer of fuel to the station took place automatically under supervision from the ground . 
 In addition to the Soyuz and Progress spacecraft , after the final crew had left , <unk> 6 was visited by an experimental transport logistics spacecraft called <unk> <unk> in 1982 . The transport logistics spacecraft , known as the <unk> , was originally designed for the <unk> programme , and proved that large <unk> could dock automatically with space stations , a major step toward the construction of <unk> stations such as <unk> and the International Space Station . 
 
