 = HMS <unk> ( 1863 ) = 
 
 HMS <unk> was an armoured frigate built for the Royal Navy in the 1860s . Upon completion in 1864 she was assigned to the Channel Fleet . The ship was paid off in 1868 to refit and be re @-@ armed . When she recommissioned in 1869 , she was assigned as the guard ship of the Fleet Reserve in the Portland District until 1874 . <unk> was refitted and re @-@ armed again in 1874 and became the guard ship of the Liverpool District in 1875 . Two years later , she was rejoined the Channel Fleet before going to the Mediterranean in 1878 . The ship returned to the Channel Fleet in 1880 and served until she was paid off in 1885 . 
 <unk> was recommissioned in 1901 as a depot ship at Malta under a succession of different names . She was transferred to Chatham in 1914 and was again renamed multiple times before she was sold for scrap in 1923 . <unk> had more changes of her rigging and armament than any other British warship , before or since . 
 
 = = Design and description = = 
 
 <unk> was the third member of the 1861 Naval Programme and was designed as an improved version of the earlier Warrior @-@ class armoured frigates with a complete waterline armour belt . 
 The ship was 380 feet 2 inches ( 115 @.@ 9 m ) long between <unk> , had a beam of 58 feet 3 inches ( 17 @.@ 8 m ) and a draft of 27 feet 2 inches ( 8 @.@ 3 m ) . She displaced 9 @,@ 820 long tons ( 9 @,@ 980 t ) and had a tonnage of 6 @,@ 121 <unk> . The hull was subdivided by <unk> transverse bulkheads into 106 compartments and had a double bottom . <unk> was designed with a high centre of gravity and was very stiff . So much so that the ship only rolled 10 degrees during one storm that ripped the main and <unk> <unk> masts off and split her <unk> . Because of her great length she was not very <unk> . <unk> had a crew of <unk> officers and enlisted men . 
 
 = = = <unk> = = = 
 
 The ship had a single two @-@ cylinder trunk steam engine made by John Penn and Sons driving a single 24 @-@ foot ( 7 @.@ 3 m ) propeller . Ten rectangular boilers provided steam to the engine at a working pressure of 25 <unk> ( 172 <unk> ; 2 <unk> / <unk> ) . During her sea trials on 15 March 1865 , <unk> had a maximum speed of 14 @.@ 32 knots ( 26 @.@ 52 km / h ; 16 @.@ 48 mph ) from 5 @,@ <unk> indicated horsepower ( 4 @,@ 267 kW ) . The ship carried 750 long tons ( 760 t ) of coal , enough to steam 1 @,@ 800 nautical miles ( 3 @,@ 300 km ; 2 @,@ 100 mi ) at 6 @.@ 5 knots ( 12 @.@ 0 km / h ; 7 @.@ 5 mph ) . 
 As built , <unk> was ship @-@ rigged with four masts , called bow , fore , main and <unk> from fore to aft , and she was the only British warship ever to have four masts . They carried a total of 44 @,@ 000 square feet ( 4 @,@ <unk> m2 ) of sail area , excluding the <unk> , the greatest area ever spread in a British warship . Her performance was unsatisfactory when the wind was before the beam and her <unk> and <unk> were removed in June 1865 in an attempt to correct this problem . However , now she had too much weather helm so the <unk> was replaced and the foremast was moved forward 25 feet ( 7 @.@ 6 m ) in July 1866 . This reduced her sail area to 30 @,@ 133 square feet ( 2 @,@ 799 m2 ) . In 1877 <unk> was <unk> as a barque . Both of her funnels were retractable to reduce wind resistance while under sail alone . 
 
 = = = Armament = = = 
 
 The intended armament of <unk> changed no less than five times before it was finally mounted . She received four rifled 110 @-@ pounder breech @-@ loading guns mounted on the upper deck , two of which served as chase guns at the bow and stern , and 16 smoothbore , muzzle @-@ loading 100 @-@ pounder Somerset cannon , eight on each side on the main deck . The breech @-@ loading guns were a new design from Armstrong and much was hoped for them . <unk> tests carried out in September 1861 against an armoured target , however , proved that the 110 @-@ pounder was inferior to the 68 @-@ pounder smoothbore gun in armour penetration and repeated incidents of breech explosions during the Battles for <unk> and the <unk> of <unk> in 1863 – 64 caused the navy to withdraw the gun from service shortly afterwards . In 1865 , six 68 @-@ pounder <unk> were added , three on each side of the main deck , although she was not <unk> <unk> until her 1868 refit . 
 Detailed data for the Somerset cannon is not available , but the 7 @.@ 9 @-@ inch ( 201 mm ) solid shot of the 68 @-@ pounder gun weighed approximately 68 pounds ( 30 @.@ 8 kg ) while the gun itself weighed 10 @,@ 640 pounds ( 4 @,@ 826 @.@ 2 kg ) . The gun had a muzzle velocity of 1 @,@ <unk> ft / s ( <unk> m / s ) and had a range of 3 @,@ 200 yards ( 2 @,@ 900 m ) at an elevation of 12 ° . The seven @-@ inch ( 178 mm ) shell of the 110 @-@ pounder Armstrong breech @-@ <unk> weighed 107 – 110 pounds ( 48 @.@ 5 – 49 @.@ 9 kg ) . It had a muzzle velocity of 1 @,@ 150 ft / s ( 350 m / s ) and , at an elevation of 11 @.@ 25 ° , a maximum range of 4 @,@ 000 yards ( 3 @,@ 700 m ) . The 110 @-@ pounder gun weighed 9 @,@ 520 pounds ( 4 @,@ <unk> @.@ 2 kg ) . All of the guns could fire both solid shot and explosive shells . 
 <unk> was <unk> during her 1867 – 68 refit with 22 seven @-@ inch and eight 8 @-@ inch ( 203 mm ) rifled muzzle @-@ loading guns . The eight @-@ inch guns and 18 seven @-@ inch guns were mounted on the main deck and the remaining seven @-@ inch guns replaced the 110 @-@ pounders on the upper deck . The shell of the 15 @-@ calibre eight @-@ inch gun weighed 175 pounds ( 79 @.@ 4 kg ) while the gun itself weighed nine long tons ( 9 @.@ 1 t ) . It had a muzzle velocity of 1 @,@ 410 ft / s ( 430 m / s ) and was credited with the ability to penetrate 9 @.@ 6 inches ( <unk> mm ) of wrought iron armour at the muzzle . The 16 @-@ calibre seven @-@ inch gun weighed 6 @.@ 5 long tons ( 6 @.@ 6 t ) and fired a 112 pounds ( 50 @.@ 8 kg ) shell . It was credited with the ability to penetrate 7 @.@ 7 @-@ inch ( 196 mm ) armour . 
 In 1874 the ship was <unk> with 16 nine @-@ inch rifled muzzle @-@ <unk> replacing the 4 eight @-@ inch and 20 of the 22 seven @-@ inch guns . Fourteen of the nine @-@ inch ( <unk> mm ) guns were mounted on the main deck and the other two replaced the seven @-@ inch chase guns . The two remaining seven @-@ inch guns stayed in their position on the quarterdeck . As the nine @-@ inch guns were considerably bigger than their predecessors , the gun ports had to be widened to accommodate them . The shell of the 14 @-@ calibre nine @-@ inch gun weighed 254 pounds ( 115 @.@ 2 kg ) while the gun itself weighed 12 long tons ( 12 t ) . It had a muzzle velocity of 1 @,@ 420 ft / s ( 430 m / s ) and was rated with the ability to penetrate a 11 @.@ 3 inches ( <unk> mm ) of wrought iron armour at the muzzle . 
 
 = = = Armour = = = 
 
 The ship had a wrought iron waterline armour belt that ran the full length of the ship . <unk> , it was 4 @.@ 5 inches ( 114 mm ) thick for a length of 212 feet ( 64 @.@ 6 m ) and tapered to a thickness of 2 @.@ 5 inches ( 64 mm ) to the ends of the ship . The armour extended 5 feet 6 inches ( 1 @.@ 7 m ) below the waterline . The main deck was protected by a <unk> of armour , also 4 @.@ 5 @-@ inch thick and 212 feet long . To protect against <unk> fire the upper <unk> was closed off by 4 @.@ 5 @-@ inch transverse bulkheads at each end . 
 
 = = Construction and service = = 
 
 <unk> , named after the Greek mythological hero , was ordered on 10 April 1861 from the Chatham Dockyard . She was the first iron @-@ <unk> warship to be built at a royal dockyard and her construction was delayed by the need to acquire the necessary machinery to handle iron and to train the workers to use it . The ship was laid down on 1 August 1861 in a <unk> and was floated out rather than being launched on 23 December 1863 . <unk> was completed on 26 November 1864 at the cost of £ <unk> @,@ <unk> . 
 She served in the Channel Fleet until 1868 . After a refit and her first major re @-@ armament , <unk> became the <unk> at Portland until 1874 when she was again re @-@ armed . Upon its completion in 1875 , the ship became <unk> at Liverpool until 1877 when Captain William <unk> , VC , assumed command . In 1878 she was one of the ships in the <unk> Service Squadron which Admiral Geoffrey <unk> took through the Dardanelles at the time of the Russian war scare in June – August 1878 during the Russo @-@ Turkish War . <unk> accidentally collided with the flagship of the Mediterranean Fleet , Alexandra , in October 1879 , but was only lightly damaged by Alexandra 's propeller . The ship rejoined the Channel Fleet in 1880 and was paid off in 1885 . 
 She lay <unk> in the <unk> until April 1901 , when she was sent to Malta as a depot ship . To release her name for the new armoured cruiser , <unk> was renamed <unk> in 1902 . She was renamed Egmont in March 1904 , and remained in Malta until 1914 . Her role in Malta was assumed by the stone frigate Fort St Angelo . She was brought home to Chatham that year , and served there as a depot ship under the successive names of <unk> ( 19 June 1916 ) and <unk> ( 6 June 1919 ) . The ship was sold for scrap on 26 January 1923 to the <unk> <unk> Co . 
 
 
 = M3 Gun Motor Carriage = 
 
 The M3 Gun Motor Carriage ( <unk> ) was a United States Army tank destroyer equipped with one 75 mm gun and was produced by <unk> . After the fall of France , the U.S. Army decided to make a self @-@ propelled artillery piece from the <unk> gun on the M3 chassis , which was designated the <unk> . After some improvement , it came into production as the M3 Gun Motor Carriage . However , the supply of <unk> gun shields was insufficient for production needs , so a new gun shield was used . This was designated the <unk> <unk> . 
 The <unk> / M3 first served in the Philippines Campaign in 1942 with the Provisional Field Artillery Brigade in the anti @-@ tank and the fire @-@ support role . It then served in North Africa in tank destroyer battalions . It was used <unk> in the Battle of <unk> Pass and several other engagements , but was used with success in the Battle of El <unk> . It also served in the Allied invasion of Sicily , but was eventually superseded by the <unk> tank destroyer . A total of 2 @,@ 203 were produced , of which 1 @,@ 361 were converted back into <unk> half @-@ tracks . 
 The M3 <unk> also served in the Pacific theater , starting with the Battle of <unk> . It proved effective against the Japanese Type 95 Ha @-@ Go and Type 97 Chi @-@ Ha tanks . It later served in the Battle of Okinawa , the Battle of <unk> and many other island battles . 
 
 = = Specifications = = 
 
 The M3 <unk> was 20 @.@ 46 feet ( 6 @.@ 24 m ) long , 6 @.@ 45 feet ( 1 @.@ 97 m ) wide , 8 @.@ 17 feet ( 2 @.@ 49 m ) high ( including the gun shield ) , and weighed 20 @,@ 000 pounds ( 9 @.@ 1 t ) . Its suspension consisted of semi @-@ elliptical <unk> leaf springs for the wheels and vertical <unk> springs for the tracks , while its transmission consisted of constant <unk> . Its ground clearance was 11 @.@ 2 inches ( 280 mm ) . 
 It had a White <unk> 147 horsepower ( 110 kW ) , 386 cubic inch ( 6 @,@ 330 <unk> ) , 6 @-@ cylinder engine with a compression ratio of 6 @.@ 44 : 1 . It had a 150 mile ( 240 km ) range , 60 US gal ( 230 l ) fuel tank , a speed of 47 mph ( 75 km / h ) , and a power to weight ratio of 14 @.@ 7 hp per ton . It was armed with one 75 mm <unk> with 59 rounds , had 0 @.@ 25 – 0 @.@ 625 in ( 6 @.@ 4 – 15 @.@ 9 mm ) of armor , and a crew of five consisting of a commander , gunner , two <unk> , and a driver . The M3 ( with the <unk> mount ) could traverse 19 ° left and 21 ° right , elevate 29 ° and depress − 10 ° . The <unk> ( using the <unk> mount ) could traverse 21 ° in both directions , but could only depress − 6 @.@ 5 ° . 
 
 = = Development = = 
 
 After the fall of France , the U.S. Army studied the reasons behind the effectiveness of the German campaign against the French and British forces . One aspect that was highlighted by this study was the use of self propelled artillery ; however , by 1941 , there was little available in the U.S. Army 's arsenal that could be used in such a role . The Army had a number of <unk> guns , sufficient enough for the mass @-@ production for such a weapon , and the M3 half @-@ track was coming into production . After some debate , the Army decided to place <unk> guns on the M3 half @-@ track chassis , which was designated the <unk> <unk> . The <unk> gun was originally adapted for the M3 chassis by placing it in a <unk> box riveted to the chassis behind the driver 's compartment . It was accepted by the Army on 31 October 1941 . 
 A batch of 36 <unk> were used for testing , while another 50 were built and transported to the Philippines . The 36 <unk> were improved in multiple ways . The improvements included the inclusion of a mount that raised the gun shield , the replacement of the original gun shield with the <unk> gun shield , and the addition of a 0 @.@ 5 in ( 12 @.@ 7 mm ) <unk> <unk> machine gun , which was later removed . After the final improvements were finished , the prototype vehicles were sent to the <unk> Company for production . 
 
 = = = <unk> = = = 
 
 As the existing supply of <unk> gun shields was insufficient to meet requirements for the production of the M3 , the Ordnance Department developed the <unk> gun shield , which replaced the <unk> . The new design was designated as the <unk> Gun Motor Carriage . 
 
 = = Service history = = 
 
 
 = = = American use = = = 
 
 The <unk> / M3 <unk> first saw action with the U.S. Army in the Philippines in 1941 – 42 , six months after it was designed . Three battalions of the Provisional Field Artillery Brigade operated <unk> against the Japanese when they invaded the Philippines . During the early part of the campaign , the vehicle was used to provide direct covering fire and anti @-@ tank support . The Japanese captured a few vehicles in 1942 and used them in the defense of the Philippines . 
 By 1942 , M3 <unk> were being used by tank destroyer battalions in the North African Campaign , each of which consisted of 36 <unk> and four 37 mm <unk> <unk> . The M3 <unk> , which were designed for <unk> tanks , proved to be inadequate for this task in the battles of <unk> <unk> <unk> and <unk> Pass , mainly due to poor tactics . Nevertheless , the M3 was later used in the Battle of El <unk> with success , claiming 30 German tanks , including possibly two Tiger tanks , at the cost of 21 <unk> . Some <unk> also saw service in Allied invasion of Sicily ( Operation <unk> ) , but by that time , the <unk> tank destroyer had replaced it in the U.S. Army . A total of 1 @,@ 360 M3 <unk> were also converted back into <unk> half @-@ tracks . 
 The M3 also served with the U.S. Marines in the Pacific Theater of Operations and was first used in the invasion of <unk> . It proved highly effective against the Type 95 Ha @-@ Go and the Type 97 Chi @-@ Ha , in the fight against the Japanese 9th Tank Regiment on <unk> . It also served in the Battle of <unk> and the Battle of Okinawa , and many other conflicts in the Pacific . 
 
 = = = Allied use = = = 
 
 The M3 <unk> saw limited service with other countries as it was not widely supplied through the <unk> @-@ <unk> program . A small batch of 170 vehicles were supplied to Britain , which used them in armored car regiments . They were first used in the <unk> Campaign with the Royal <unk> . They were also used in Sicily , Italy , and later in France , but were gradually retired . The Free French Army also used <unk> for training before receiving <unk> tank destroyers . 
 
 = = Production = = 
 
 A total of 2 @,@ 202 M3 <unk> were produced from 1941 to 1943 . Only 86 vehicles were produced in 1941 , but this was increased in 1942 during which 1 @,@ 350 examples came off the production lines . A further <unk> were completed in 1943 . Production was stopped due to the release of better tank destroyers , like the <unk> <unk> . 
 
 
